[White "?"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]

1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Ne4?! {This move loses a pawn for no compensation or leads to a serious weakening of the kingside.} 3.d4 {White threatens to trap the knight on e4 with f3.} 3...e6 {Black prevents the immediate f3 with the threat Qh4 and also prepares an escape route for the knight.} 4.Nh3! {White renews the threat of trapping the knight with f3.} 4...h6 5.Qg4 {White wins a pawn now.} 5...d5 6.f3 h5 7.Qf4 g5 {This is the only move which saves the knight.} 8.Nxg5 Nxg5 9.Qxg5 {White is simply a pawn up.}  *

[Event "2...Ng8 2"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "?"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]

1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Ng8 {Playable but slightly worse than Nd5.} 3.d4 d6 4.f4 (4.Nf3 { is of course good as well.}) 4...Bf5 5.Nf3 {Another good option is} (5.Bd3 Bxd3 6.Qxd3 e6 7.Nf3) 5...e6 6.Bd3 Ne7 7.O-O dxe5 8.fxe5 Nbc6 9.c3 {with a clear plus for White. The pawn on c3 stops Black's counterplay. This is the reason why Black usually tries to     'lure' the pawn to c4 by playing Nd5 on move 2.}  *

