1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 c5 4.c4 Nb4 (4...Nc7 5.dxc5 { ±  White is a pawn up.}) 5.d5 d6 6.a3 N4a6 7.Bf4 (7.Nf3 { and} (7.f4 { are good as well. After f4 Black's best option is probably to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop and go for setups similar to those in the 5...g6 chapter. In comparison to the lines there Black's knight is even further offside but he has not wasted any time with the light squared bishop.}) { I like Bf4 here best because it gives White the option of castling queenside  (after Qd2 and Nc3)  and also because it avoids Bg4 which would be possible after Nf3.}) 7...Nd7 8.Nf3 {White is better. White can complete his development with Nc3, Qe2, O-O-O or Be2 and O-O while it is not so easy for Black to find good squares for his pieces.}  *

