1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The simplest way to deal with various move orders is just to remember     to answer Bf5 with Nc3, Nc6 with Be3, e6 with Nf3 and dxe5 with fxe5.} 5...e6?! 6.Nc3 d5 (6...dxe5 7.fxe5 c5 8.d5 { transposes to the chapter         6...c5,e6}) 7.c5 N6d7 8.b4 b6 9.Rb1± {White has a large space advantage and Black has difficulties finding squares for his pieces.}  *

