1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The simplest way to deal with various move orders is just to remember to answer Bf5 with Nc3, Nc6 with Be3, e6 with Nf3 and dxe5 with fxe5.} 5...c5?! {gives White a clear advantage.} 6.dxc5 N6d7 {Black sacrifices a pawn because the endgame after dxc5 is rather depressing for Black.} (6...dxc5 7.Qxd8+ Kxd8 8.Nc3 { followed by Be3, O-O-O and Ne4}) 7.cxd6 exd6 8.exd6 Nf6 9.Qe2+ Be6 10.Nc3 {Necessary because the tempting} (10.f5 { drops a pawn after} 10...Qa5+ {.}) 10...g6 (10...Nc6 11.c5 g6 12.Nf3 { followed by Ng5 gives White         a large advantage.}) (10...Bxd6 ? 11.f5 O-O 12.fxe6 Re8 13.Be3 Rxe6 14.O-O-O { +-  White is simply a piece up.}) 11.f5 gxf5 12.Bg5 {followed by O-O-O is much better for White.}  *

