1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The simplest way to deal with various move orders is just to remember     to answer Bf5 with Nc3, Nc6 with Be3, e6 with Nf3 and dxe5 with fxe5.} 5...Bf5 {this usually tranposes to the mainline.} 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.Be3 e6 8.Nf3 Be7 9.Be2 (9.d5 { is possibly a little bit stronger than Be2 but         aiming for a transposition to the mainlines is simpler.} 9...exd5 10.cxd5 Nb4 11.Nd4 Bc8 12.Bb5+ c6 13.dxc6 O-O 14.e6 { +=}) 9...O-O (9...dxe5 10.fxe5 { transposes to the  chapter 9...Be7  (chapter:11)  (.)}) 10.O-O d5 (10...dxe5 11.fxe5 { transposes to the  chapter 9...Be7  (chapter:11)  (.)}) 11.c5 Nc4 12.Bxc4 dxc4 13.Qa4 Bd3 14.Rfd1 a5 15.a3 {followed by Ne1 is a bit better for White. Black can attack the center with f6, but then Black will be left with a weak pawn on d3 after:} 15...f6 16.Ne1 fxe5 17.Nxd3 cxd3 18.dxe5 {The pawn on d3 is not easy to defend after Qc4 or Qe4.}  *

