1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The simplest way to deal with various move orders is just to remember     to answer Bf5 with Nc3, Nc6 with Be3, e6 with Nf3 and dxe5 with fxe5.} 5...Bf5 {this usually tranposes to the mainline.} 6.Nc3 e6 7.Nf3 Be7 8.Be3 (8.Bd3 Bg4 9.h3 dxe5 10.dxe5 { is an independent option 	and may in fact even slightly stronger than transposing to the 	mainlines. White gets the bishop pair, a space advantage but a 	less dynamic pawn center than he gets in the mainlines.}) 8...O-O 9.Bd3 {is perhaps slightly better for White than the usual mainlines since Black cannot put any pressure on the center.} (9.Be2 dxe5 10.fxe5 { transposes to the  chapter 9...Be7  (chapter:11)  (.)})  *

