1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The simplest way to deal with various move orders is just to remember     to answer Bf5 with Nc3, Nc6 with Be3, e6 with Nf3 and dxe5 with fxe5.} 5...Bf5 {this usually tranposes to the mainline.} 6.Nc3 dxe5 7.fxe5 e6 (7...Nc6 8.Be3 e6 9.Nf3 { transposes to the mainline.}) 8.Nf3 Bb4 (8...Nc6 9.Be3 { transposes to the mainline.}) (8...Be7 9.Be2 { also transposes to the main lines after Nc6 or O-O and Nc6 by Black.}) 9.a3 {Simplest. Since retreating with the bishop just gives White the     useful move a3 for free, Black is 'forced' to take on c3 after which     attacking the center with c5 loses its sting.} (9.Bd3 { is also good for White but the position gets     rather complicated after} 9...c5) 9...Bxc3+ 10.bxc3 Nc6 11.Bd3 Bxd3 12.Qxd3 {followed by O-O is better for White.}  *

