1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 g5 {The Planinc gambit. Black wants to undermine the support of e5.} 6.Nc3 {The most flexible move.} 6...Bg7 7.Nf3 gxf4 8.Bxf4 Nc6 {still the best move in a difficult situation.} 9.exd6 {White's idea is simple. Take on d6 to give Black no targets for     counterplay in the center. Then play Qd2, O-O-O and Bh6 after which     the dark squares on Black's kingside will be seriously weakened.} (9.c5 { Is another good line for White.} 9...dxc5 10.dxc5 Qxd1+ 11.Rxd1 Nd7 { Now White's pawns look overextended but     counterattacking c7 gives White an advantage.} 12.Nd5 O-O (12...Kd8 ? 13.e6 { +-}) 13.Nxc7 Rb8 14.e6 Nxc5 15.exf7+ Rxf7 16.Bc4 e6 17.g3) 9...exd6 10.Qd2 Bg4 11.O-O-O Bxf3?! {Black goes for the pawn on d4.} (11...O-O { transposes to  10...O-O  (variation:9119363/#/11/b)  (.)}) 12.gxf3 Qd7 13.Re1+ Ne7 14.Rg1+- {White should be winning soon.     Black's king is stuck in the center and the bishop on g7 has no good     squares.} 14...Bf8 (14...Rg8 15.Bh6) (14...Bf6 15.Ne4) 15.Bg5 (15.c5 { is probably even stronger but also more complicated.})  *

