1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 g5 {The Planinc gambit. Black wants to undermine the support of e5. If White takes on g5 with the f-pawn then Black gets a comfortable position. But if White just develops naturally then he gets an advantage.} 6.Nc3 {The most flexible move.} 6...Bg7 7.Nf3 {White has other good moves as well, for instance Qh5, but I decided to keep it simple. Note that White can play Nf3 here without worrying about Bg4.} 7...gxf4 (7...g4 { Black forces the knight to the edge but the knight is not badly placed on h4. It stops Bf5 and can later be rerouted via g2.} 8.Nh4 dxe5 9.fxe5 c5 { The only way to put pressure on White's center. After other moves White can play Be3 or c5 with a clear advantage.} 10.d5 { White has to sacrifice the pawn on e5 but in return gets a large lead in development and a strong attack.} 10...Qc7 (10...Bxe5 11.Bd3 Bf6 12.Nf5 Bxf5 13.Bxf5 e6 14.Qe2 { White will regain the pawn at the very least with a dominating position.}) 11.Be2 Qxe5 12.g3 Bf6 13.Ng2 Na6 14.Bf4 Qh5 15.Qd2 { +-  Black's extra pawn is meaningless. White's minor pieces are well placed and Black's king will have trouble finding a safe spot.}) (7...Bg4 8.h3 { the simplest move. Since retreating to f5 or h5 runs into g4 Black has to take on f3.} 8...Bxf3 9.Qxf3 dxe5 10.dxe5 { This is one of the few instances where recapturing with the d-pawn is the right choice. Here it is simply necessary o avoid losing a pawn.} Nc6 11.g3 { Keeping Black's dark-squared bishop out of the game.} 11...gxf4 12.gxf4 Nd4 13.Qe4 f5 14.Qd3 e6 15.Be3 { +-  The bishop pair, the space advantage and the fact that both the knight on b6 and the bishop on g7 are currently not doing anything give White a clear advantage.}) 8.Bxf4 Nc6 {The best move in a difficult situation.} (8...Bg4 9.h3 Bxf3 (9...Bh5 10.g4 Bg6 11.Qe2 dxe5 12.dxe5 c5 13.Rd1 Qc8 14.Bg2 O-O 15.O-O { +-  White is clearly better. The threat of Nd5 and e6 is difficult to defend against.}) 10.Qxf3 dxe5 11.dxe5 { +-  White has a lead in development, the bishop pair, targets on b7 and g7 and a clear plan to improve his position further with Qg3, Qd1, Be2 or Bd3 and O-O. For example} 11...Nc6 12.Qg3 Kf8 13.Rd1 Qc8 14.Be2 { White's position looks winning after moves like Ne4, O-O and Bg4.}) (8...Bf5 9.Bd3 Qd7 (9...Bxd3 10.Qxd3 Nc6 11.exd6 cxd6 12.O-O e5 13.Be3 { White is much better. The half-open f-file and the outpost on f5 are very much in White's favor compared to similar positions with addition pawns on g6 and f2,}) (9...Bg4 10.h3 Bh5 11.Qe2 Nc6 12.g4 Bg6 13.O-O-O { +-  White threatens e6 and c5.}) 10.O-O Bxd3 11.Qxd3 Nc6 12.exd6 cxd6 13.Rae1 { +-  With the usual advantages for White. Better pawn structure, space, safer king, more active light pieces.}) (8...dxe5 9.Bxe5 Bxe5 10.Nxe5 { White is much better. f7 is weak and Black's king can not easily get to safety. Castling short looks suicidal and preparing to castle long will take a while.}) 9.exd6 {White's idea is simple. Take on d6 to give Black no targets for      counterplay in the center. Then play Qd2, O-O-O and Bh6 after which      the dark squares on Black's kingside will be seriously weakened.} 9...exd6 (9...cxd6 10.Qd2 O-O 11.Bh6 { threatening Qg5.} 11...Bxh6 12.Qxh6 e5 13.O-O-O Qe7 14.d5 Nb4 15.g4 { Anticipating f5.} 15...f5 { Otherwise      White gets a crushing attack with Rg1, Nh4-f5.} 16.g5 { followed by g6      and Rg1 with a strong attack.}) 10.Qd2 Bg4 (10...O-O 11.O-O-O Bg4 12.Bh6 Qf6 13.Bxg7 Qxg7 14.h3 Bxf3 15.gxf3 { followed by h4-h5-h6 or Be2 and Rhg1 or Rh2-g2. In all cases White      will have the faster attack.}) (10...Qe7+ 11.Kf2 O-O 12.Re1 Qf6 13.Bg5 Qg6 14.Bd3 Qh5 15.h3 { followed by g4 or} 15...f5 (15...Nxd4 16.g4 { is winning}) 16.Ne2 { and White is much better after Nf4.}) 11.O-O-O Bxf3 {Black goes for the pawn on d4.} (11...O-O { transposes to 10...O-O.}) 12.gxf3 {White has a large advantage here.} 12...Bxd4 (12...Qd7 13.Re1+ Ne7 14.Rg1 { White should be winning soon. Black's king is stuck in the center and the bishop on g7 has no good squares.} 14...Bf8 15.Bg5) (12...Nxd4 13.Bh6 Bxh6 14.Qxh6 Ne6 15.c5 Nd7 16.Ne4 Nexc5 17.Nxc5 Nxc5 18.Bb5+ c6 19.Rxd6 { and Black can resign.}) 13.Re1+ Be5 14.c5 Nd7 15.cxd6 cxd6 16.Qxd6 {White is winning.}  *

