1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 g6 {This is the modern way to play against the Four Pawns Attack, although it was already played by Reti in 1925. Black plans to play Bg7 and Be6 and if White plays d5, then Black can play Bf5 followed by c6.} 6.Nc3 dxe5 {This exchange is a little bit     premature. White can now play c5 without having to worry about dxc5.} 7.fxe5 Bg7 (7...c5 8.d5 { transposes to  6... c5  (chapter:4)}) 8.c5 {White gains more space and more importantly stabilizes the     center because Black's main attacking idea, the move c5, is no longer     possible.} 8...N6d7 9.Bc4 e6 10.Nf3 h6 11.O-O O-O 12.Be3 {White can start a strong attack with Qd2 and Ne4. Since most of Black's pieces are far away from the kingside it is not clear how Black should defend.}  *

