1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 g6 {This is the modern way to play against the Four Pawns Attack, although it was already played by Reti in 1925. Black plans to play Bg7 and Be6 and if White plays d5, then Black can play Bf5 followed by c6.} 6.Nc3 Bg7 7.Be3 Be6 {The modern main line.} 8.Rc1 {White will have to play d5 sooner or later to fight for an advantage.     If White plays d5 too early then Black can get rid of White's center     pawns with c6. So White wants to play d5 only after Black has attacked     the center with c5. But as soon Black castles the pawn on c4 will be     hanging. So White prepares b3 by protecting the knight on c3 which     otherwise would be undefended on the long diagonal after b3 and d5.} 8...Nxc4 9.Qa4+ Qd7 10.Bxc4 Qxa4 11.Nxa4 Bxc4 12.Rxc4 b5 13.Rxc7⩲ {with a very unpleasant endgame for Black.}  *

