1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 g6 {This is the modern way to play against the Four Pawns Attack, although it was already played by Reti in 1925. Black plans to play Bg7 and Be6 and if White plays d5, then Black can play Bf5 followed by c6.} 6.Nc3 Bg7 7.Be3 Be6 {The modern main line.} 8.Rc1 {White will have to play d5 sooner or later to fight for an advantage.     If White plays d5 too early then Black can get rid of White's center     pawns with c6. So White wants to play d5 only after Black has attacked     the center with c5. But as soon Black castles the pawn on c4 will be     hanging. So White prepares b3 by protecting the knight on c3 which     otherwise would be undefended on the long diagonal after b3 and d5.} 8...O-O 9.b3 dxe5 (9...c5 10.d5 { will very likely transpose since delaying dxe5 only gives White extra options.} 10...Bc8 (10...Bf5 11.Be2 { followed by Nf3 and O-O.}) 11.Nf3 { followed by Be2 and O-O. Once Nf3 has been played White has the additional option to recapture on e5 with the knight.}) 10.fxe5 c5 11.d5 Bf5 12.Be2 {White prevents Nd7 with this move because g4 would trap the bishop if     there is a knight on d7.} (12.Nf3 ?! N8d7 { allows Black to comlete his development     and put pressure on White's center.}) 12...Na6 {Black protects c5 but gives White enough time to protect     e5 in return.} 13.Bf4 Qc7 14.Nb5 Qb8 15.Nf3± {followed by O-O and Qd2. If Black tries to put more pressure on e5 then White has d6 and after f6 both exf6 or Bg3 are good for White.}  *

