1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black     play cxd4 then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for     White.} 7.d5 {avoiding the exchange and also preventing Nc6.} 7...e6 {Black now uses d5 as a new target.} 8.Nc3 Qh4+ {The only alternative to exd5. Other moves are simply too slow because they allow White to stabilize the center with Nf3.} 9.g3 Qd4 10.Qxd4 cxd4 11.Nb5± {followed by d6 and Nbxd4 with an extra pawn and a better position for White.}  *

