1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black     play cxd4 then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for     White.} 7.d5 {avoiding the exchange and also preventing Nc6.} 7...e6 {Black now uses d5 as a new target.} 8.Nc3 exd5 9.cxd5 {The starting point of this line. If Black can develop his pieces, especially the bishop on f8, then the pawns on e5 and d5 may become difficult to defend. If, on the other hand, White manages to prevent Black from developing for long enough then the extra space may be used to start an attack.} 9...Bf5 {Black develops but does not put any     pressure on White's center. White is much better after} 10.Nf3 c4 11.d6±  *

