1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black     play cxd4 then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for     White.} 7.d5 {avoiding the exchange and also preventing Nc6.} 7...e6 {Black now uses d5 as a new target.} 8.Nc3 exd5 9.cxd5 {The starting point of this line. If Black can develop his pieces,     especially the bishop on f8, then the pawns on e5 and d5 may become     difficult to defend. If on the other hand White manages to prevent     Black from developing for long enough then the extra space may be used     for starting an attack.} 9...c4 {Black wants to put more pressure on White's center with Bb4 or target     White's dark squares on the kingside with Bc5.} 10.d6 {The key move. White is much better now because Black cannot break up     White's dominating pawns in the center. White's plan is     straightforward: complete development with Bf4, Nf3 and Be2. If Black     attacks the center too early with f6 then Nb5 with the threat Nc7+ is     strong.} 10...Nc6 (10...Be6 11.Nf3 Nc6 12.Bf4 { transposes to the  mainline  (variation:9119503/#/12/w)}) 11.Bf4 {In this position Black's can try to break up White's pawns on e5 and     d6 with f6 or fianchetto his dark-squared bishop with h6 and g5.} 11...f6 {Black tries to break down White's center     immediately.} 12.Nb5 fxe5 13.Be3 Qh4+ 14.g3 Qe4 15.Nc7+ Kd8 16.Qe2! Qxh1?! {gives White a clear advantage after the forced         line} 17.Bg5+ Kd7 18.O-O-O Bxd6 19.Nb5 {taking on a8 is good as well but Nb5 wins the Black queen.} 19...Nd4 20.Bh3+ Kc6 21.Nxd4+ exd4 22.Bg2+ {and Black does not get enough material in exchange for the queen.}  *

