1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black     play cxd4 then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for     White.} 7.d5 {avoiding the exchange and also preventing Nc6.} 7...e6 {Black now uses d5 as a new target.} 8.Nc3 exd5 9.cxd5 {The starting point of this line. If Black can develop his pieces,     especially the bishop on f8, then the pawns on e5 and d5 may become     difficult to defend. If on the other hand White manages to prevent     Black from developing for long enough then the extra space may be used     for starting an attack.} 9...c4 {Black wants to put more pressure on White's center with Bb4 or target     White's dark squares on the kingside with Bc5.} 10.d6 {The key move. White is much better now because Black cannot break up     White's dominating pawns in the center. White's plan is     straightforward: complete development with Bf4, Nf3 and Be2. If Black     attacks the center too early with f6 then Nb5 with the threat Nc7+ is     strong.} 10...Nc6 (10...Be6 11.Nf3 Nc6 12.Bf4 { transposes to the mainline}) 11.Bf4 {In this position Black's can try to break up White's pawns on e5 and     d6 with f6 or fianchetto his dark-squared bishop with h6 and g5.} 11...Be6 12.Nf3 {Now after the light-squared bishop has moved we play Nf3.} 12...f6 (12...h6 13.Nd4 { ±  followed by Be2, Ne4 and O-O with a     clear advantage for White.}) 13.Nd4 Qd7 14.Be2 O-O-O 15.Ne4 {White simply makes sure that d6 is sufficiently defended  (and also threatens Nc5)  .} 15...Nxd4 16.Qxd4 {White is much better. Black's problem is that White can easily defend the pawn on d6 and that means the bishop on f8 and the rook on h8 will remain spectators for quite a bit longer. In the meantime White can castle either side, pick up the pawn on c4 and win a pawn on f6  (fxe5 does not help Black, after Bxe5 Black still cannot develop his kingside)  .}  *

