1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Be7 10.Be2 (10.d5 exd5 11.cxd5 Nb4 12.Nd4 { is a complicated line     which involves an exchange sacrifice by White but does not promise     White any advantage.}) 10...O-O (10...Bg4 11.O-O O-O { transposes to  9...Be7 10.Be2 O-O 11.O-O Bg4  (variation:9119566/#/11/b)  (.)}) 11.O-O f6 12.exf6 Bxf6 13.Qd2 Qe7 14.Rad1 Rad8 15.Kh1 {Necessary to avoid e5.} (15.Qc1 { A popular move but inaccurate because Black has a     promising pawn sacrifice.} 15...e5 16.d5 Nd4 17.Bxd4 (17.Nxd4 exd4 18.Bxd4 Bg5 19.Qa1 Na4 20.Bf3 Be3+ 21.Bxe3 Qxe3+ 22.Kh1 Nxc3 { does not promise White anything.}) exd4 18.Nxd4 Bg5 19.Qa1 Bd7 { The bishop pair and White's weakened     dark squares give Black sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 15...Bg4 {This was suggested by Ametanoitos on chesspub. I think     White is better after} 16.Ne4 Bxf3 17.Nxf6+ Rxf6 18.gxf3 Qf7 (18...e5 19.d5 { ±}) 19.b3 h6 {Black wants to play Ne5 but since the immediate Ne5 allows     Bg5 Black has to play h6 first.} 20.Rg1 {threatening Bxh6} 20...Kh8 21.Qc2 {not allowing Ne5.} 21...Ne7 22.Qe4 Nf5 23.Bc1 {followed by Bb2     and Bd3. White is clearly better. I don't see how Black can neutralize     the bishops.}  *

