1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Be7 10.Be2 (10.d5 exd5 11.cxd5 Nb4 12.Nd4 { is a complicated line     which involves an exchange sacrifice by White but does not promise     White any advantage.}) 10...O-O (10...Bg4 11.O-O O-O { transposes to  9...Be7 10.Be2 O-O 11.O-O Bg4  (variation:9119566/#/11/b)  (.)}) 11.O-O f6 12.exf6 Bxf6 13.Qd2 Qe7 14.Rad1 Rad8 15.Kh1 {Necessary to avoid e5.} (15.Qc1 { A popular move but inaccurate because Black has a     promising pawn sacrifice.} 15...e5 16.d5 Nd4 17.Bxd4 (17.Nxd4 exd4 18.Bxd4 Bg5 19.Qa1 Na4 20.Bf3 Be3+ 21.Bxe3 Qxe3+ 22.Kh1 Nxc3 { does not promise White anything.}) exd4 18.Nxd4 Bg5 19.Qa1 Bd7 { The bishop pair and White's weakened     dark squares give Black sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 15...h6 16.Qc1 Kh8 (16...Rd7 17.Bg1 Rfd8 { too early. With the king still on     g8 White can play} 18.d5 exd5 19.cxd5 { because the pawn is indirectly     protected. If Black takes then White can win an exchange with Bc4.}) 17.h3 Rd7 18.Bg1 (18.d5 Ne5 19.b3 Nxf3 20.Bxf3 exd5 21.Rde1 { has been         played but Black has equalized here. If White takes on d5 with the         knight then Black has solved the problem of the knight on b6 and         after cxd5 the pawn can become weak. In the latter case Nc8-d6 is         also possible.}) 18...Rfd8 {As far as I am concerned this is the key position in this     line. If White protects d4 with Qf4 then Black can increase the     pressure on d4 with g5 and Qg7. So the next move is more or less     forced.} 19.c5! Nc8 20.Bb5 a6 21.Bxc6 bxc6 22.Rde1 {gives White a clear advantage after Ne4 or Ne2-f4.}  *

