1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Be7 10.Be2 (10.d5 exd5 11.cxd5 Nb4 12.Nd4 { is a complicated line     which involves an exchange sacrifice by White but does not promise     White any advantage.}) 10...O-O (10...Bg4 11.O-O O-O { transposes to  9...Be7 10.Be2 O-O 11.O-O Bg4  (variation:9119566/#/11/b)  (.)}) 11.O-O f6 12.exf6 Bxf6 13.Qd2 Qe7 14.Rad1 Rad8 15.Kh1 {Necessary to avoid e5.} (15.Qc1 { A popular move but inaccurate because Black has a     promising pawn sacrifice.} 15...e5 16.d5 Nd4 17.Bxd4 (17.Nxd4 exd4 18.Bxd4 Bg5 19.Qa1 Na4 20.Bf3 Be3+ 21.Bxe3 Qxe3+ 22.Kh1 Nxc3 { does not promise White anything.}) exd4 18.Nxd4 Bg5 19.Qa1 Bd7 { The bishop pair and White's weakened     dark squares give Black sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 15...h6 16.Qc1 Kh8 (16...Rd7 17.Bg1 Rfd8 { too early. With the king still on     g8 White can play} 18.d5 exd5 19.cxd5 { because the pawn is indirectly     protected. If Black takes then White can win an exchange with Bc4.}) 17.h3 Bh7 {The most popular move but I think increasing the pressure on d4 with     Rd7 and Rfd8 is more logical.} 18.Bg1 Rd7 19.Rfe1 Qd8 (19...Rfd8 20.d5 exd5 21.cxd5 Nxd5 { The attempt to prevent the knight on c3 from recapturing on d5} (21...Bxc3 22.bxc3 Nxd5 { loses an exchange after} 23.Bb5 Qf6 24.Bxc6 bxc6 25.Bd4 Qf4 26.Ne5 Qxc1 27.Rxc1 Re7 28.Bc5 {.}) 22.Rxd5 Rxd5 23.Nxd5 Rxd5 24.Bc4 { White has a clear advantage.}) 20.Qe3 Qe7 21.Bf1⩲  *

