1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 (9.Be2 { If White wants to avoid the 9...Bg4 lines then     this move order is also possible. Starting with 9. Be2 means that     White can no longer choose the sharp 10. d5 line against Be7 and also     that in the Nb4 line can no longer choose 11. Qb3.} 9...Qh4+ { The only     independent option.} 10.Bf2 Qe7 11.a3 (11.Nf3 ?! Qb4 { is a bit uncomfortable for White.}) O-O-O 12.Nf3 { White is a bit better after c5 and b4.}) 9...Bg4 10.Be2 Bxf3 {If Black does not take now the the game will transpose to other     lines.} 11.gxf3 Qh4+ 12.Bf2 Qf4 13.c5 {White wants to exchange queens. But doing so immediately helps Black     to get counterplay.} (13.Qc1 ?! Qxc1+ 14.Rxc1 O-O-O 15.Rd1 Bb4 16.a3 (16.O-O ? Bxc3 17.bxc3 Na5 18.c5 Nd5 19.Rc1 { =+  Black's knights         get too active.}) Bxc3+ 17.bxc3 Na5 18.c5 Nd5 19.Kd2 =) 13...Nd7 14.Qc1⩲ {Now we can exchange queens with a very good endgame for White since the knight on d7 blocks the d-file and Black cannot put  pressure on d4 quickly enough. The bishop pair and the large space advantage are quite useful when playing on both wings as is the case here. Also it is not easy for the black knights to find good squares.} (14.Bb5 { is certainly playable. The engines also like this move. But after playing c5 I believe that the ability to cover the light squares is worth more than the doubled pawns on c7 and c6 Black is likely to get.}) (14.b4 O-O-O 15.b5 { is quite interesting. Black's best option is probably} Ncxe5 16.dxe5 Nxe5 { White seems to be better here as well but the position is rather complicated.}) 14...Qxc1+ {The retreat} (14...Qf5 { is covered in the game  Chandra-Lenderman  (variation:9448520)  (.)}) 15.Rxc1 {White's space advantage, the bishop pair and Black's difficulties in making use of the outpost on d5 are all points in White's favor. White can put the pawn on f4 to stabililze the center, move the bishops to f3 and e3 and then push the pawns on the queenside.}  *

