1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Qd7 10.Be2 O-O-O (10...Be7 11.O-O { transposes to 9...Be7.}) (10...Bg4 11.O-O { transposes to 9...Be7, 10...Rd8, or     11...Bg4 depending on Black's next move.}) 11.O-O Kb8 {The best move as far as I am concerned. Black prevents tactics along     the c8-h3 diagonal before deciding how to continue.} 12.a4 {White threatens to push back the knight on b6 after which the central break d5 can no longer be prevented. If Black stops the a-pawn by playing a5 himself then the pawn on a5 can become a target and the knight on b6 loses half of its support. If the pawn on c7 is pinned by a queen on g3 or takes a pawn on d6  (after d5-d6 by White)  the knight on b6 can easily fall prey to the bishop on e3. 

White has other moves as well but 12.a4 looks strongest to me.} (12.d5 ? exd5 13.Bxb6 axb6 14.cxd5 Bc5+ 15.Kh1 Nb4 { is fine for Black. With the king on b8 there are no tactics along the     h3-c8 diagonal.}) (12.Qe1 Nb4 13.Rd1 Nc2 14.Qf2 Nxe3 15.Qxe3 { is an engine favorite. I am not so convinced that White should give up the bishop pair, but White has a stable space advantage and without the knight on c6 Black can not put pressure on White's center.}) (12.a3 { I like this move but now think that 12.a4 is stronger.} 12...f6 (12...Bg4 13.c5 Nd5 14.Nxd5 Qxd5 15.h3 { is very similar to 11...Bg4.}) 13.b4 fxe5 14.Nxe5 Nxe5 15.dxe5 { +=  is slightly better for White as well.}) 12...Bb4 13.a5 Bxa5 14.Qb3± {followed by Rfd1 and d5 or c5 is much better for White. Black's minor pieces are providing convenient targets to speed up White's attack.}  *

