1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Qd7 10.Be2 Rd8 11.O-O (11.Qd2 { Postponing castling in order to be ready to     answer Bg4 with Rd1 is also possible. This will probably transpose to     the 9...Be7 system after Be7 and O-O by Black but it does give Black     the additional option} 11...Bg4 12.Rd1 Bxf3 13.gxf3 { White is better     here as well but I prefer O-O.}) 11...h6 12.Qd2 Be7 13.Rad1 {and it seems that     Black has nothing better to transpose to the 9...Be7 system with O-O     and f6. However, after} 13...O-O {White can also play} 14.Bxh6! gxh6 15.Qxh6± {with a strong attack. The immediate threat is Ng5, Rxf5 and Qh7 mate. If Black captures the knight then White recaptures with the queen followed by Rf3. So Black's best defense is to stop Ng5 with f6:} (15...f6 16.c5 { White wants to weaken Black's pressure on d4 before playing Nh4.} 16...Nd5 17.Nh4 Nxd4 { Black has Bxc5 in case of Rxd4.} (17...Bh7 18.Rf3 { wins for White.}) 18.Nxf5 Nxf5 (18...Nxe2+ 19.Kh1 { followed by a rook lift is winning. For instance:} 19...exf5 20.Qg6+ Kh8 21.Nxd5 fxe5 22.Rd3) 19.Qg6+ Ng7 20.Nxd5 fxe5 21.exf6 { and White wins back the piece with an ongoing attack.})  *

