1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Qd7 10.Be2 Rd8 11.O-O (11.Qd2 { Postponing castling in order to be ready to     answer Bg4 with Rd1 is also possible. This will probably transpose to     the 9...Be7 system after Be7 and O-O by Black but it does give Black     the additional option} 11...Bg4 12.Rd1 Bxf3 13.gxf3 { White is better     here as well but I prefer O-O.}) 11...Be7 12.d5 {White is much better already.} 12...exd5 13.Bxb6 {A common motif. White ensures that Black cannot recapture on     d5.} 13...axb6 14.cxd5 Nb4 15.Nd4 Bc5 16.Kh1 {The threats Nxf5 and e6 as well as         Black's somewhat lose minor pieces give White a clear advantage.} 16...Bxd4 (16...Bg6 17.e6 { +-}) 17.e6! {Better than the immediate Qxd4 because it gives White the additional option of Bh5+ and as bonus stops g6 as well.} 17...fxe6 18.Qxd4 {White plans to play Bh5+ next. As long as the         queen is on d4 Black cannot block the check with g6 because White         could take the rook on h8, so Black has to either move the king or         play Bg6 opening the f-file.} 18...Nxd5 19.Bh5+ Bg6 20.Bxg6+ hxg6 21.Nxd5+- {Black             cannot recapture with the queen because of Qxg7, nor with the             pawn because of Rae1+.}  *

