1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Qd7 10.Be2 Rd8 11.O-O (11.Qd2 { Postponing castling in order to be ready to     answer Bg4 with Rd1 is also possible. This will probably transpose to     the 9...Be7 system after Be7 and O-O by Black but it does give Black     the additional option} 11...Bg4 12.Rd1 Bxf3 13.gxf3 { White is better     here as well but I prefer O-O.}) 11...Bg4 12.b3 {White secures c4 to be ready to recapture on f3 with bishop, after     which d4 will be indirectly protected because b7 hangs as well. Both     12. c5 and 12. Ng5 are playable as well. But these lines are more     complicated without giving White a larger advantage.} (12.d5 { leads to unclear play after} 12...Bxf3 (12...Na5 13.Ng5) 13.Bxf3 Nxe5 14.c5 Nxd5 15.Nxd5 exd5 16.Bd4 f6) 12...Bxf3 13.Bxf3 Nxd4 14.Bxb7 c5 (14...Bb4 15.Ne4 { followed by Qg4 gives White a strong attack.}) 15.Be4 {followed by Qg4, Rae1 and, if necessary, Kh1 leaves Black     without counterplay.}  *

