1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Bb4 {Black's idea is to put pressure on White's queenside before White can     consolidate. One point is that if Black continues with Na5 then White     cannot defend c4 with the natural looking move because the knight on     c3 would be hanging.} 10.Be2 {White develops normally.} (10.Rc1 { is interesting as well. Tillis gives} 10...Bg4 11.a3 Bxc3+ 12.bxc3 O-O 13.Bd3 Bxf3 14.gxf3 Qh4+ 15.Bf2 Qh3 { as     annoying for White but after} 16.Rg1 { I would rather be White. Black's     queen can become a target Rg4-h4 and trying to open lines against     the White king with} 16...f6 17.Rg4 { threatening Rh4 and Bxh7+} 17...g6 18.Rh4 Qg2 19.Qd2 { looks very dangerous for Black. White threatens     Qh6 and Bxg6, and Ke2 followed by Rg1 is also possible.}) 10...O-O {This is playable but it makes White job     a bit easier because the knight on c3 is no longer pinned.} (10...Bxc3+ 11.bxc3 { will transpose to one of the other     lines.}) 11.O-O Bxc3 12.bxc3 Ne7 (12...Na5 13.c5 Nd5 14.Bd2 { transposes to  11... Na5  (variation:9119659/#/14/w)  (.)}) 13.Nh4 Be4 14.Qd2 c5 15.Rf4 {followed by Raf1 and a very pleasant         position for White.}  *

