1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Bb4 {Black's idea is to put pressure on White's queenside before White can     consolidate. One point is that if Black continues with Na5 then White     cannot defend c4 with the natural looking move because the knight on     c3 would be hanging.} 10.Be2 {White develops normally.} (10.Rc1 { is interesting as well. Tillis gives} 10...Bg4 11.a3 Bxc3+ 12.bxc3 O-O 13.Bd3 Bxf3 14.gxf3 Qh4+ 15.Bf2 Qh3 { as     annoying for White but after} 16.Rg1 { I would rather be White. Black's     queen can become a target Rg4-h4 and trying to open lines against     the White king with} 16...f6 17.Rg4 { threatening Rh4 and Bxh7+} 17...g6 18.Rh4 Qg2 19.Qd2 { looks very dangerous for Black. White threatens     Qh6 and Bxg6, and Ke2 followed by Rg1 is also possible.}) 10...O-O {This is playable but it makes White job     a bit easier because the knight on c3 is no longer pinned.} (10...Bxc3+ 11.bxc3 { will transpose to one of the other     lines.}) 11.O-O Na5 12.c5 Bxc3 {forced because the knight on c3 is no longer pinned.} (12...Nd5 13.Nxd5 { followed by a3 traps the bishop.}) 13.bxc3 Nd5 14.Bd2 {White is threatening to win a piece with c4.} 14...Ne7 15.Nh4 {White is better bishop pair, space advantage, stable center, half open b-file after the bishop on f5 gets exchanged. For instance} 15...Be4 16.Rf4 Bd5 17.Bd3 {with a strong attack.}  *

