1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Bb4 {Black's idea is to put pressure on White's queenside before White can     consolidate. One point is that if Black continues with Na5 then White     cannot defend c4 with the natural looking move because the knight on     c3 would be hanging.} 10.Be2 {White develops normally.} (10.Rc1 { is interesting as well. Tillis gives} 10...Bg4 11.a3 Bxc3+ 12.bxc3 O-O 13.Bd3 Bxf3 14.gxf3 Qh4+ 15.Bf2 Qh3 { as     annoying for White but after} 16.Rg1 { I would rather be White. Black's     queen can become a target Rg4-h4 and trying to open lines against     the White king with} 16...f6 17.Rg4 { threatening Rh4 and Bxh7+} 17...g6 18.Rh4 Qg2 19.Qd2 { looks very dangerous for Black. White threatens     Qh6 and Bxg6, and Ke2 followed by Rg1 is also possible.}) 10...Na5 {Probably Black's best move. Black threatens c4 before White is ready     to defend it with b3.} (10...Bxc3+ 11.bxc3 { will transpose to one of the other     lines.}) 11.c5 Nd5 (11...Bxc3+ 12.bxc3 Nd5 13.Bd2 { transposes to 12...Bxc3}) 12.Bd2 Ne7 13.O-O O-O {In this position Tillis only considers 14. a3 which is a mistake I     believe. The square a3 is needed by White's dark-squared bishop to     answer b6 with Ba3 neutralizing Black's counterplay on the queenside.} 14.Bc1! {A key move in this line. White threatens to trap the bishop with Nc3-b1 and a3 and keeps the square a3 for the bishop to be ready to answer b6 with Ba3.} 14...Qe8 15.Bb5 {White wants Black to block the retreat for the     knight on a5.} 15...c6 16.Bd3 Bxc3 17.bxc3 Nd5 18.Bxf5 exf5 19.Qa4 {Black has problems with the knight stranded on a5.}  *

