[Result "*"]

1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...Bf5 {This is likely to transpose to the mainline but Black has     an independent option here.} 6.Nc3 e6 7.Nf3 Na6 {Baburin's move. Black     wants to attack White's center with c5.} 8.a3 (8.Bd3 { is also good but I think a3 is just as good         and much simpler.}) 8...c5 9.dxc5 dxc5 (9...Nxc5 10.b4 Ne4 11.Nxe4 Bxe4 12.exd6 { followed by         c5 is much better for White.}) 10.Qe2 {with the idea Be3, Qf2, Be2 and O-O and a very comfortable game for White. Black's knights have difficulties getting into the game.}  *

[Event "Quickstarter 5"]
