[Result "*"]

1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...g5 {Planinc's ultra-sharp response to the four pawns attack. As     long as White continues developing and refrains from taking on g5     with the f-pawn he should be quite a bit better.} 6.Nc3± {White     simply continues developing. Taking on g5 would give Black a     comfortable position after dxe5.} 6...Bg7 7.Nf3 {White has other good moves as well, for instance Qh5, but I decided to keep it simple.} 7...g4 (7...gxf4 8.Bxf4 Nc6 9.exd6 exd6 10.Qd2 { with the better game for White. He can continue with O-O-O and Bh6.}) (7...Bg4 { is not a problem for White here.} 8.h3 Bxf3 9.Qxf3 dxe5 10.dxe5 { is better for White.}) 8.Nh4 {and the knight on h4 is actually rather well placed. It     prevents the development of Black's light-squared bishop and supports     pushing the f-pawn. Also supporting the pawn on g4 with h5 may weaken     the g6-square.} 8...dxe5 9.fxe5 c5 10.d5 {White sacrifices a pawn to     keep the center closed and make it difficult for Black to develop his     queenside.} 10...Bxe5 11.Bd3 Bf6 12.g3 (12.Nf5 { is equally good.}) 12...N8d7 13.O-O {White has more     than enough compensation for the pawn.}  *

