1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...g6 {The modern mainline} 6.Nc3 Bg7 7.Be3 {White protects d4 without allowing the pin Bg4 which would be possible after the natural looking Nf3.} 7...Be6 {Black does not     fear d5. The bishop simply retreats and after c6 Black can eliminate     White's center.} 8.Rc1 {White protects the knight on c3 to be able to     play b3 to support c4 without having to worry about tactics involving     the unprotected knight on c3.} 8...dxe5 9.fxe5 Nxc4 {Now White gets a better position after the         following forced moves.} 10.Bxc4 Bxc4 11.Qa4+ b5 12.Nxb5 Bxb5 13.Qxb5+ Nd7 {otherwise Qb7 is strong.} 14.Nf3 {Black's pawns on a7         and c7 are weak and activating the bishop on g7 is not easy. Both         sides will probably castle short next.}  *

