1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...g6 {The modern mainline} 6.Nc3 Bg7 7.Be3 Be6⩲ {Black does not     fear d5. The bishop simply retreats and after c6 Black can eliminate     White's center.} 8.Rc1 {White protects the knight on c3 to be able to     play b3 to support c4 without having to worry about tactics involving     the unprotected knight on c3.} 8...O-O 9.b3 {White will keep a small advantage. If Black takes on e5     White recaptures with the f-pawn and c5 can be answered by d5. White's     plan is to play Be2, Nf3 and O-O. For example} 9...dxe5 10.fxe5 c5 11.d5 Bf5 12.Be2 {White prevents either knight from going to d7 because     then g4 would trap the bishop.} 12...Bxe5 13.Nf3 {Here we see why Rc1     was useful.} 13...Bxc3+ 14.Rxc3 N8d7 15.O-O {with a clear advantagefor White. White can attack with Bh6, Ng5 and perhaps even g4 or Rxf5.Black's dark squares are weak and the knight on b6 and the rook on a8 are still out of play.}  *

