1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...dxe5 6.fxe5 Bf5 {This move usually transposes to the mainline unless Black     postpones Nc6 in favor of a quick c5.} 7.Nc3 e6 8.Nf3 Bb4 {Black wants     to play c5 quickly to make use of the pin. While the knight is pinned     White cannot answer c5 with d5.} 9.a3 {The simplest answer. Either     White gets the move a3 for free or Black has to take on c3 after which     the attack with c5 loses most of its power. 9. Bd3 is also possible     but quite complicated.} 9...Bxc3+ 10.bxc3 c5 11.Bd3 {White is better. Black cannot put much pressure on White's center pawns and White can try to make use of the square d6.}  *

