1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 {White protects d4 without allowing the pin Bg4 which would be     possible after the natural looking Nf3.} 7...Bf5 8.Nc3 {Here we see another benefit of playing Be3 on the previous move.     White can now answer Nb4 with Rc1.} 8...e6 {Black has to complete his development.} 9.Nf3 {The tabiya of the Four Pawns Attack. About half the games starting with 5 f4 reach this position at the master level. Black has now 5 major choices. In roughly decreasing order of popularity these choices are: Be7, Bg4, Qd7, Bb4 and Nb4.} 9...Nb4 {The riskiest move for Black. Black wins a tempo to free his     c-pawn and attack the center with c5.} 10.Rc1 c5 11.Be2± {Now Black     has two choices the risky cxd4 or the attempt to complete his     development with Be7.} 11...Be7 12.a3 cxd4 13.Nxd4 Nc6 14.Nxf5 exf5 15.O-O {followed by c5 and b4 gives White a long lasting advantage. The bishop pair and the mobile pawns on the queenside will be difficult to contain.}  *

