1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 {White protects d4 without allowing the pin Bg4 which would be     possible after the natural looking Nf3.} 7...Bf5 8.Nc3 {Here we see another benefit of playing Be3 on the previous move.     White can now answer Nb4 with Rc1.} 8...e6 {Black has to complete his development.} 9.Nf3 {The tabiya of the Four Pawns Attack. About half the games starting with 5 f4 reach this position at the master level. Black has now 5 major choices. In roughly decreasing order of popularity these choices are: Be7, Bg4, Qd7, Bb4 and Nb4.} 9...Bg4 {Black plays Bg4 with a loss of tempo. The idea is that after the natural Be2 Black can capture on f3 and White has to     recapture with the g-pawn or be willing to sacrifice the pawn on c4.} 10.Be2 Bxf3 11.gxf3 Qh4+ 12.Bf2 Qf4 {Black plans to castle queenside next with pressure against d4. Exchanging queens immediately with Qd2 or Qc1 is playable but not best.} 13.c5! {An important move to remember. If     the knight jumps to d5 we can take on d5 and Black is forced to     recapture with the pawn after which there is no more pressure against     White's center.} 13...Nd7 14.Qc1 {Now we can exchange queens with a very good endgame for White since the knight on d7 blocks the d-file and Black cannot put  pressure on d4 quickly enough. The bishop pair and the large space advantage are quite useful when playing on both wings as is the case here. Also it is not easy for the black knights to find good squares.} (14.Bb5 { is certainly playable. The engines also like this move. But after playing c5 I believe that the ability to cover the light squares is worth more than the doubled pawns on c7 and c6 Black is likely to get.}) (14.b4 O-O-O 15.b5 { is quite interesting. Black's best option seems to be} Ncxe5 16.dxe5 Nxe5 { when White is probably better, but the position is rather complicated.})  *

