1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 {White protects d4 without allowing the pin Bg4 which would be     possible after the natural looking Nf3.} 7...Bf5 8.Nc3 {Here we see another benefit of playing Be3 on the previous move.     White can now answer Nb4 with Rc1.} 8...e6 {Black has to complete his development.} 9.Nf3 {The tabiya of the Four Pawns Attack. About half the games starting with 5 f4 reach this position at the master level. Black has now 5 major choices. In roughly decreasing order of popularity these choices are: Be7, Bg4, Qd7, Bb4 and Nb4.} 9...Bb4 10.Be2 Na5 {This is the point of Bb4. Now b3 is impossible because the knight on c3 would lose its protection.} 11.c5 Nd5 12.Bd2 Ne7 13.O-O O-O {The     line suggested by Tillis in his course here on chessable. I believe     Black has problems after White's next move.} 14.Bc1⩲ {White's     threat is Na4, or even Nb1 followed by a3 trapping the bishop. So     Black has to take on c3.} 14...Bxc3 15.bxc3 {Here we see the point of White's maneuver. If White had played 14.a3 then Black would be more or less ok after b6. But with the pawn still on a2 and the bishop on c1 White can answer b6 with Ba3 being ready to recapture on c5 with the bishop in case Black plays bxc5. Other moves by Black give White a free hand to attack on the kingside.}  *

