1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 {White protects d4 without allowing the pin Bg4 which would be     possible after the natural looking Nf3.} 7...Bf5 8.Nc3 {Here we see another benefit of playing Be3 on the previous move.     White can now answer Nb4 with Rc1.} 8...e6 {Black has to complete his development.} 9.Nf3 {The tabiya of the Four Pawns Attack. About half the games starting with 5 f4 reach this position at the master level. Black has now 5 major choices. In roughly decreasing order of popularity these choices are: Be7, Bg4, Qd7, Bb4 and Nb4.} 9...Qd7 {Black wants to immediately put pressure on d4 with O-O-O or     Rd8. But here White gets the better position after Be2 and O-O.} 10.Be2 O-O-O 11.O-O Kb8 {In my opinion this is the best move for Black. It avoids tactics on the diagonal h3-c8.} 12.a4 a5 {For me this is one of the key positions in the Qd7 and O-O-O line. This is one of the lines I was hoping to play when looking at the Aljechin from the Black side. White has two good setups to choose from. 

One is to play Qb3, Rac1, Rfd1 and then Nb5 and perhaps d5 and d6 to make use of the vulnerability of the knight on b6  (cxd6 can leave the knight on b6 undefended)  . 

The other  (and the choice for this repertoire)  is to transfer the queen to g3 via e1 from where it can defend the pawn on e5  (useful when trying to play the pawn break d5)  and also indirectly eyeing the king on b8. While the queen is on e1 there are also tactics involving Nb5 and Qxa5, even if Black can win an exchange with Nb4-c2xa1 in a few lines.} 13.Qe1 Bb4 {The complications after} (13...Nb4 14.Nb5 { are in White's favor. See the chapter on 9...Qd7 and O-O-O for details, but note that it is essential to include the moves a4 and a5.}) 14.Qg3 f6 15.d5 Nxe5 (15...exd5 16.Bxb6 cxb6 17.cxd5 { is much                 better for White.}) 16.Nxe5 fxe5 17.Na2 {White threatens Nxb4 followed by a5 as             well as d6 or dxe6.} 17...Qe7 18.Nxb4 Qxb4 19.Qxe5 {White is better. The pawn on g7 is hanging, the bishop on f5 is in trouble after dxe6 and d6 is a strong threat as well. The ipoint of d6 is that cxd6 leaves the knight on b6 without protection and taking on d6 with a piece runs into the fork c5.}  *

