1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 {White protects d4 without allowing the pin Bg4 which would be     possible after the natural looking Nf3.} 7...Bf5 8.Nc3 {Here we see another benefit of playing Be3 on the previous move.     White can now answer Nb4 with Rc1.} 8...e6 {Black has to complete his development.} 9.Nf3 {The tabiya of the Four Pawns Attack. About half the games starting with 5 f4 reach this position at the master level. Black has now 5 major choices. In roughly decreasing order of popularity these choices are: Be7, Bg4, Qd7, Bb4 and Nb4.} 9...Qd7 {Black wants to immediately put pressure on d4 with O-O-O or     Rd8. But here White gets the better position after Be2 and O-O.} 10.Be2 Rd8 11.O-O Bg4 12.b3 {I like this simple move. It keeps the knight on b6 out of the game and plans to start an attack with Ne4, Kh1, Qe1 and     Rad1. The only question is whether Black can risk taking the pawn on d4 after Bxf3. In case you are worried I believe the answer is no.} 12...Bb4 (12...Bxf3 13.Bxf3 Nxd4 14.Bxb7 { is good for White.}) 13.Ne4 O-O (13...Bxf3 14.Bxf3 Nxd4 15.Bh5 { is very good for White         because the g-pawn needs to protect f6.}) 14.Kh1 Be7 (14...Bxf3 15.Rxf3 { This time we take with the rook.} 15...Nxd4 16.Rh3 { followed by Qb1 or Qc2 if the knight retreats to         f5 and a great attacking position.}) 15.Qe1 Bxf3 {otherwise White plays Rd1 and is simply better.} 16.Rxf3 Nxd4 17.Rh3 Nxe2 18.Qxe2 {again with a nice attack. Black will get problems on the dark squares once he is forced to play g6.}  *

