1.e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine defence was introduced by Alexander Alekhine almost 100 years ago. Black allows White to gain several tempi attacking by advancing pawns to attack the knight. Black plans to regain the lost tempi by forcing White to first defend and later exchange these pawns. Once Black succeeds in doing this he may be able to exploit the weakened squares in the center which White can no longer defend with pawns. White on the other hand can try to use his space advantage to start an attack     and also to make use of Black's misplaced knight on b6.} 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The starting point of the Four Pawns Attack. If White can secure his center he will be better. Black's counterplay is based one the slight difficulty White has in defending the d-pawn. After Nf3, Black can play Bg4 and pushing the d-pawn to d5 can leave the pawn on e5 undefended if the exchange dxe5 fxe5 has been played. But with precise play White can defend the center and keep an advantage.} 5...dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 {White protects d4 without allowing the pin Bg4 which would be     possible after the natural looking Nf3.} 7...Bf5 8.Nc3 {Here we see another benefit of playing Be3 on the previous move.     White can now answer Nb4 with Rc1.} 8...e6 {Black has to complete his development.} 9.Nf3 {The tabiya of the Four Pawns Attack. About half the games starting with 5 f4 reach this position at the master level. Black has now 5 major choices. In roughly decreasing order of popularity these choices are: Be7, Bg4, Qd7, Bb4 and Nb4.} 9...Be7 10.Be2 (10.d5 !? { leads to sharp and unclear variations in which White has to sacrifice an exchange. White gets compensation but not more. I do not recommend to play this move unless you are well prepared. I do not believe that these lines give any advantage to White, so I recommend the quieter Be2 here.}) 10...O-O 11.O-O f6 {Without this move Black will find it difficult to get any     counterplay.} 12.exf6 Bxf6 {White is a bit better here as long as he does not allow Black to play     e5 to free his game.} 13.Qd2 Qe7 14.Rad1 Rad8 {Here White has tried many moves but I believe Kh1 is the most     precise.} 15.Kh1⩲ (15.Qc1 { is also a popular move, but it is not so good in my opinion because it allows Black to play e5. The following line is just an example but it shows how useful the check on the a7-g1 diagonal can be. Thus, my preference for Kh1.} 15...e5 16.d5 Nd4 17.Nxd4 exd4 18.Bxd4 Bg5 19.Qa1 Na4 ! 20.Bf3 Be3+ 21.Bxe3 Qxe3+ 22.Kh1 Nxc3 23.bxc3)  *

