1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The most important rule concerning move orders in the Four Pawns Attack is 

POSTPONE Nf3 AS LONG AS POSSIBLE.

This almost always means wait for Black's light-squared bishop to move at least once before playing Nf3, because otherwise the pawn on d4 may be difficult to defend after Bg4. 
If Black is aiming for a classical setup agains the Four Pawns Attack then Black usually plays dxe5, Bf5, Nc6 and e6 in some order or other. The simplest way for White to handle the different move orders is to always answer 
- dxe5 with fxe5, 
- Bf5 with Nc3, 
- Nc6 with Be3 and 
- e6 with Nf3. 
White wants to play Nf3, Be2 and O-O as quickly as possible but has to be bit careful.} 5...dxe5 {Black increases the pressure on d4 and also ensures that the pawn on e5 is no longer defended by a pawn in case White plays d5, so that moves like Nxe5 become possible. Also, if e6 has been played then dxe5 opens the diagonal for the bishop on f8.} 6.fxe5 {Almost always the right recapture. There are only a few lines in which dxe5 is the better option. Most of the lines in which dxe5 is better than fxe5 are lines in which the latter move would immediately lose the pawn on d4. If Black delays dxe5 for too long then Nxe5 may also be good. But these cases are rare.} 6...Nc6 {With Nc6 Black puts pressure on d4, but abandons the idea of a quick c5. See the chapter on 9...Nb4 for reasons why going for a quick c5 after Nc6 is probably not so good.} 7.Be3 {Defending d4 with Nf3 can lead to problems after Bg4 especially if      Black has not played Bf5 yet and can play Bg4 in one move saving a      tempo. So Be3 is the natural answer. If Black's bishop is already on      f5 then Nc6 also threatens Nb4 and then the natural defence Rc1 is      only available if Nc3 and Be3 have been played already. Note that Nc6      only makes sense after dxe5 has been played because otherwise White      can simply play d5 without having to worry about Nxe5.} 7...Bf5 {Essentially Black's only sensible move here.} (7...g6 ?! { The fianchetto only makes sense if Black can also play c5     to attack White's center. With the knight on c6 this is impossible.} 8.Be2 Bg7 9.Nf3 O-O 10.O-O Bg4 11.Nbd2 { ±  White is better here because attacking White's center with f6 does not work well in this position.} f6 ?! 12.e6 ! { A typical response. The pawn is indirectly protected because of the fork d5.} Bxe6 13.d5 Nxd5 14.cxd5 Bxd5 { Black has gotten three pawns for the piece but it is not so easy to get these pawns moving after} 15.Nb1 ! Bf7 16.Qa4 e5 17.Nc3 { with moves like Rad1, Bc4 or Bb5, Bc5 coming next.}) 8.Nc3 {Preparing to answer Nb4 with Rc1.} 8...e6 {Opening the path for Black's dark-squared bishop. This move is      necessary unless Black fianchettos this bishop.} (8...Nb4 9.Rc1 c5 10.Nf3 e6 { transposes to 9... Nb4}) 9.Nf3 {As far as move orders are concerned White has only one choice to make: whether to play Be2 before or after Nf3 in the mainline. If White starts with Be2 then Black can no longer play 9... Bg4 in the standard move order. But White also deprives himself of some aggressive options against 9...Nb4 or 9...Be7 with the move 9. Be2. I only consider 9. Nf3 here because I do not see a reason for avoiding 9... Bg4, and also because Black can choose non-standard move-orders 5...Bf5 and e6 in which delaying Nf3 is not advisable for White.} (9.Be2 { transposes to the mainlines after Be7, Bb4, Nb4 or Qd7 if White continues with Nf3.}) 9...Be7 10.Be2 O-O {The most common move. Black can still transpose to the 9...Qd7 systems with Qd7 and Rd8 or O-O-O, or to the Nb4 system with Nb4 and c5. The latter avoids White's most dangerous  but also rather complicated option 9...Nb4 10. Rc1 c5 11. Qb3. I recommend 11.Be2 instead of 11. Qb3 in this repertoire in order not to have to worry about this move order.} 11.O-O f6 12.exf6 Bxf6 13.Qd2⩲ {This is the tabiya of the classical mainline in the Four Pawns Attack.}  *

