1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The most important rule concerning move orders in the Four Pawns Attack is 

POSTPONE Nf3 AS LONG AS POSSIBLE.

This almost always means wait for Black's light-squared bishop to move at least once before playing Nf3, because otherwise the pawn on d4 may be difficult to defend after Bg4. 
If Black is aiming for a classical setup agains the four pawns attack then Black usually plays dxe5, Bf5, Nc6 and e6 in some order or other. The simplest way for White to handle the different move orders is to always answer 
- dxe5 with fxe5, 
- Bf5 with Nc3, 
- Nc6 with Be3 and 
- e6 with Nf3. 
White wants to play Nf3, Be2 and O-O as quickly as possible but has to be bit careful.} 5...dxe5 {Black increases the pressure on d4 and also ensures that if White plays d5 that the pawn on e5 is no longer defended by a pawn so that moves like Nxe5 become possible. Also, if e6 has been played then dxe5 opens the diagonal for the bishop on f8.} (5...Bf5 { One of many good move orders for Black, especially if Black wants to play the 9...Bg4 line.} 6.Nc3 { The standard answer. White wants to be ready to answer Nc6 and Nb4 with Be3 and Rc1 after Black exchanges on e5.} e6 { This is the move order Black can choose if he wants to play the 9... Bg4 system without giving White the option to avoid this line because here 7. Nf3 is White's best move.} (6...Nc6 ?! { should only be played after dxe5} 7.d5 Nb4 8.g4 ! Nc2+ 9.Kf2 Nxa1 10.gxf5 { White is winning because the knight on a1 is trapped.}) (6...dxe5 7.fxe5 { This transposes to the mainline.}) 7.Nf3 { The best move here and the reason why White cannot avoid the 9...Bg4 system in the classical mainline.} (7.Be2 ?! { This move gives Black the extra option of playing a Bb4 system where attacking White's center with c5 is still possible.} 7...dxe5 8.fxe5 Bb4 { and I don't think White has any advantage after either c5 or O-O followed by c5.}) 7...dxe5 (7...Na6 { Black plans to attack the center with c5.} 8.a3 { White has time to stop Nb4 and Bb4 because Black did not put any pressure on White's center.} 8...c5 9.dxc5 dxc5 10.Qe2 { White is better.}) (7...Be7 { Here Black did not put any pressure on White's center so any natural developing move, like Be2, Be3 or Bd3 is good.} 8.Bd3 { The simplest solution.} 8...Bxd3 9.Qxd3 Nc6 10.O-O { White is better. Black has less pressure on the central pawns than in the mainline.}) 8.fxe5 Nc6 (8...Bb4 { is Black's last chance to avoid the main lines but White is better after} 9.a3) 9.Be3 { And once again we are back in the mainline.}) 6.fxe5 {Almost always the right recapture. There are only a few lines in which dxe5 is the better option. Most of the lines in which dxe5 is better than fxe5 are lines in which the latter move would immediately lose the pawn on d4. If Black delays dxe5 for too long then Nxe5 may also be good. But these cases are rare.} 6...Bf5 7.Nc3 {The standard answer to Bf5. White wants to be ready to answer Nc6 with Be3 and Nb4 with Rc1.} 7...e6 (7...Nc6 8.Be3 { transposes to the mainline.}) 8.Nf3 Be7 (8...Bb4 9.Bd3 ! { and White is better because if Black tries to win a pawn with} 9...Bg4 ? 10.O-O Bxf3 11.Qxf3 Qxd4+ { then White wins after} 12.Be3 ! Qd7 13.Rad1) 9.Be2 O-O 10.O-O f6 11.Be3 Nc6 (11...fxe5 12.Nxe5 { is better for White.}) 12.exf6 Bxf6 13.Qd2⩲ {and we transposed to the tabiya of the classical mainline in the four     pawns attack.}  *

