1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 {The most important rule concerning move orders in the Four Pawns Attack is 'POSTPONE Nf3 AS LONG AS POSSIBLE' which almost always means wait for Black's light-squared bishop to move at least once before playing Nf3, because otherwise the pawn on d4 may be difficult to defend after Bg4.} 5...g6 {In this line there are not so many move order issues but the Be2 vs. Nf3 question is relevant here as well.} 6.Nc3 {White postpones Nf3 here and in the following moves for two reasons. One is of course avoiding Bg4 but the other is that in order to play d5 the long diagonal has to be secured with Be3 and Rc1.} 6...Bg7 7.Be3 Be6 {Black's tries to tempt White into playing d5 because after Bc8 followed by c6 Black would get quite a bit of counterplay.} 8.Rc1 {Pushing the pawn to d5 too early would allow Black to liquidate the center with a quick c6.} (8.b3 { is also possible. After} 8...dxe5 9.fxe5 c5 10.d5 { we get a position similar to our mainline. I believe that the omission of the moves O-O and Rc1 is slightly in Black's favor. Although White gets the extra option of protecting the knight with Qd2 instead of Rc1 and possibly even castle queenside, Black can use the tempo saved by omitting castling to get counterplay in the center more quickly.}) 8...O-O 9.b3 {White has to protect the pawn on c4 because Qa4 no longer comes with check after Black has castled.} 9...dxe5 (9...c5 10.d5 { will very likely transpose since delaying dxe5 only gives White extra options.} 10...Bc8 (10...Bf5 11.Be2 { followed by Nf3 and O-O, or}) 11.Nf3 { followed by Be2 and O-O both leave Black with nothing better than to transpose to 9...dxe5.}) 10.fxe5 c5 11.d5 {Here we see why White had to prepare for tactics on the long diagonal. Also note that we play d5 only after Black has played c5 and attacking the pawn on d5 with c7-c6 is no longer possible.} 11...Bc8 (11...Bf5 12.Be2 ! (12.Nf3 ?! N8d7 { allows Black to complete his development and put quite a bit of pressure on White's center.}) 12...N8d7 ? { Now a mistake because} 13.g4 ! { traps the bishop on f5.}) 12.Nf3 {With the bishop on c8 White does not need to fear Nd7.} (12.Be2 { is possible as well but for now it seems to me that Black gets enough counterplay.}) 12...Bg4 13.Bxc5 {With a small plus for White.}  *

