1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Ne4?! {This loses a pawn for no compensation     or leads to a serious weakening of the kingside.} 3.d4 {White threatens to trap the knight on e4 with f3.} 3...f6 {This move looks rather ugly but it prepares the escape route g5-f7 for the knight.} 4.Nh3 d5 (4...fxe5 5.dxe5 { followed by Bd3, Nf4 and perhaps Qh5 gives White a clear advantage.}) 5.f3 Bxh3 6.fxe4 Be6 7.c4 c6 (7...dxe4 8.d5 Bc8 9.e6 { ±  White simply continues with Nc3, Be3, Qd2, O-O-O with an overwhelming position.}) 8.Nc3 dxe4 9.d5 {followed by e6 and a clear advantage for White.}  *

[Result "*"]

1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Ng8 {Playable but slightly worse than Nd5.} 3.d4 d6 4.f4 (4.Nf3 { is of course good as well.}) 4...Bf5 5.Nf3 {Another good option is} (5.Bd3 Bxd3 6.Qxd3 e6 7.Nf3) 5...e6 6.Bd3 Ne7 7.O-O c5 8.Nc3 Bxd3 (8...cxd4 9.Nb5 dxe5 10.fxe5 { White has a clear advantage because Black has to move his knight from e7 to protect d6 and allow White to take on f5.}) 9.Qxd3 cxd4 (9...d5 { stabilizes the center but loses a pawn after} 10.Qb5+ { followed by Qxc5 or Qxb7.}) 10.Nb5 dxe5 (10...Ng6 11.exd6 Bxd6 12.Qxd4 { also gives White a clear advantage.}) 11.fxe5 Nf5 12.Ng5 {White has too many threats: 13.g4, 13.Rxf5 exf5 14.Qxf5, 13.Ne4 and Nd6+.}  *

[Result "*"]

1.-- {This chapter discusses the move orders available for Black  (and a few options for White)  and what White can do to avoid being tricked into systems he does not want to play. 

Even if you do not look at the remainder of this chapter please do remember this rule: postpone Nf3 as long as possible unless you know why you need to play it in the given position.}  *

[Event "10...Bf5 1"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "?"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]

1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black  attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black play cxd4  then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for White.} 7.d5 g6 {This is the modern way to play the 6...c5 variation. Originally 7...e6  was the only move played.} 8.Nc3 Bg7 9.Bf4 {White postpones the  development of the knight on g1 until  Black's light-squared bishop has  moved to avoid the pin Bg4 or at least to win a tempo.} 9...O-O 10.Qd2 {White still does not allow Bg4 and prepares to castle queenside.} 10...Bf5 (10...N8d7 11.Nf3 { White has a clear advantage. Black cannot put      any additional pressure on White's center.}) (10...Bg4 { preventing O-O-O for one move.} 11.h3 { White has a      clear advantage, after the bishop retreats and White castles long.}) 11.h3 {White prepares to trap the bishop with g4 in case Black plays e6.} 11...N8d7 (11...e6 12.O-O-O { Again White has to wait with playing g4 since      Black could play Qh4+ and after the exchange of queens the bishop can      escape via c2 and a4.}) 12.Nf3 {White could play g4 immediately but since Black can free the  bishop with the pawn sacrifice g5, White first develops. Now g4 is  threatened and is not clear how Black should defend.} 12...Qc7 13.Qe3 {does not change anything.}  *

