1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black  attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black play cxd4  then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for White.} 7.d5 g6 {This is the modern way to play the 6...c5 variation. Originally 7...e6  was the only move played.} 8.Nc3 Bg7 9.Bf4 {White postpones the  development of the knight on g1 until  Black's light-squared bishop has  moved to avoid the pin Bg4 or at least to win a tempo.} 9...O-O 10.Qd2 {White still does not allow Bg4 and prepares to castle queenside.} 10...e6 (10...N8d7 11.Nf3 { White has a clear advantage. Black cannot put     any additional pressure on White's center.}) (10...Bg4 { preventing O-O-O for one move.} 11.h3 { White has a      clear advantage, after the bishop retreats and White castles long.}) 11.O-O-O f6 12.Nf3 exd5 13.cxd5 fxe5 14.Bxe5 Bxe5 15.Nxe5 {White is  clearly better. Black is behind in development and developing his  queenside is difficult. Bf5 runs into g4 and d7 is needed by the knight on b8. Also the d-pawn cannot be blockaded on d5 because Qd6 runs into one of Nc4, Nb5 or Ne4.}  *

