1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black  attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black play cxd4  then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for White.} 7.d5 g6 {This is the modern way to play the 6...c5 variation. Originally 7...e6  was the only move played.} 8.Nc3 Bg7 9.Bf4 {White postpones the  development of the knight on g1 until  Black's light-squared bishop has  moved to avoid the pin Bg4 or at least to win a tempo.} 9...O-O 10.Qd2 {White still does not allow Bg4 and prepares to castle queenside.} 10...e6 (10...N8d7 11.Nf3 { White has a clear advantage. Black cannot put     any additional pressure on White's center.}) (10...Bg4 { preventing O-O-O for one move.} 11.h3 { White has a      clear advantage, after the bishop retreats and White castles long.}) 11.O-O-O exd5 12.cxd5 {The key position of this line. If Black plays too slowly then White can play h3, possibly g4, Nf3 and Bh6 with a strong  attack.} 12...Na6 13.h3 {White can continue with Nf3, g4 and Bh6.} 13...Nb4 (13...Bd7 { is covered in the game  Gomez Esteban-Seret  (variation:9447833)  (.)}) 14.g4 {stopping Bf5} 14...Bd7 {Black has other options  here as well, but White is always better. If Black plays calm moves then  Nf3 and Be2 are good moves for White. If Black plays Rc8 then White has  Kb1 to avoid tactics on the c-file. If Black tries to attack the center  with f6 then e6 is a good answer. For instance} (14...f6 15.e6 f5 { Black wants to activate the bishop on g7 even      at the cost of shutting in the bishop on c8.} 16.Re1 N6xd5 { loses a      piece but the threat e7 had to be dealt with.} 17.e7 Nxe7 18.Qxd8 Rxd8 19.Rxe7 { Black has insufficient compensation for the piece.}) 15.Nf3 {White is better. White can complete his development with Be2 an  then start to attack with Bh6 and Bxg7.} 15...Rc8 {does not change  anything after} 16.Kb1 {because White simply sidesteps all tactics on the c-file possible for instance after c4 and Nd3+ before completing his  development with Be2.}  *

