1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black  attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black play cxd4  then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for White.} 7.d5 g6 {This is the modern way to play the 6...c5 variation. Originally 7...e6  was the only move played.} 8.Nc3 Bg7 9.Bf4 {White postpones the  development of the knight on g1 until  Black's light-squared bishop has  moved to avoid the pin Bg4 or at least to win a tempo.} 9...O-O 10.Qd2 {White still does not allow Bg4 and prepares to castle queenside.} 10...e6 (10...N8d7 11.Nf3 { White has a clear advantage. Black cannot put     any additional pressure on White's center.}) (10...Bg4 { preventing O-O-O for one move.} 11.h3 { White has a      clear advantage, after the bishop retreats and White castles long.}) 11.O-O-O exd5 12.cxd5 {The key position of this line. If Black plays too slowly then White can play h3, possibly g4, Nf3 and Bh6 with a strong  attack.} 12...Bg4 13.Re1 c4 {preparing for Bf5-d3} 14.h3 Bf5 15.g4 (15.Nf3 Na6 16.d6 { is also good for White but I believe 15.g4 is      simpler}) 15...Bd7 16.Bh6 {Black has no counterplay whatsoever.}  *

