1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black  attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black play cxd4  then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for White.} 7.d5 g6 {This is the modern way to play the 6...c5 variation. Originally 7...e6  was the only move played.} 8.Nc3 Bg7 9.Bf4 {White postpones the  development of the knight on g1 until  Black's light-squared bishop has  moved to avoid the pin Bg4 or at least to win a tempo.} 9...O-O 10.Qd2 {White still does not allow Bg4 and prepares to castle queenside.} 10...e6 (10...N8d7 11.Nf3 { White has a clear advantage. Black cannot put     any additional pressure on White's center.}) (10...Bg4 { preventing O-O-O for one move.} 11.h3 { White has a      clear advantage, after the bishop retreats and White castles long.}) 11.O-O-O exd5 12.cxd5 {The key position of this line. If Black plays too slowly then White can play h3, possibly g4, Nf3 and Bh6 with a strong  attack.} 12...Bg4 13.Re1 c4 {preparing for Bf5-d3} 14.h3 Bf5 15.g4 (15.Nf3 Na6 16.d6 { is also good for White but I believe 15.g4 is      simpler}) 15...Bd3 16.Bxd3 cxd3 17.Qxd3 {White is a pawn up and Black does not  have sufficient compensation. White can defend the fourth rank with Re4  stopping the Black knights and the pawn on e5 can be supported with Nf3.  If Black plays Rc8 then stepping out of the pin with Kb1 avoids all  potential problems on the c-file.} 17...Nc6 18.a3 {stopping Nb4.} 18...Rc8 19.Kb1 Na5 {Black wants to put a knight on c4, then double  heavy pieces on the c-file and then play Nxb2 or Nxa3 to remove or divert  the protection of the knight on c3. Also now the exchange sacrifice on c3  is a threat. Black would get a pawn and attacking chances for the  exchange.} 20.d6 {Now the exchange sacrifice doe not make sense any  longer because there is no more Nxd5.} 20...Nac4 21.Nf3 {Simple  development but also protecting the key pawn on e5.} 21...Rc5 22.Re2 {White wants to put one rook on the e-file to protect e5 and one on the c-file to protect the knight on c3. Also, one rook should move to the second rank to avoid the rooks getting in each other's way and to give the White king some extra protection as well. This means the rooks should be on e2 and c1 or on e1 and c2. So White should play Rh2 and Rc2 or Re2 and Rc1.} 22...Qc8 {threatening Nxa3} 23.Rc1 {White has defended against all of  Black's threats and can now either continue to attack on the kingside  starting with Ne4 or push the center pawns with Nd4 and e6.}  *

