1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black  attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black play cxd4  then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for White.} 7.d5 g6 {This is the modern way to play the 6...c5 variation. Originally 7...e6  was the only move played.} 8.Nc3 Bg7 9.Bf4 {White postpones the  development of the knight on g1 until  Black's light-squared bishop has  moved to avoid the pin Bg4 or at least to win a tempo.} 9...O-O 10.Qd2 {White still does not allow Bg4 and prepares to castle queenside.} 10...e6 (10...N8d7 11.Nf3 { White has a clear advantage. Black cannot put     any additional pressure on White's center.}) (10...Bg4 { preventing O-O-O for one move.} 11.h3 { White has a      clear advantage, after the bishop retreats and White castles long.}) 11.O-O-O exd5 12.cxd5 {The key position of this line. If Black plays too slowly then White can play h3, possibly g4, Nf3 and Bh6 with a strong  attack.} 12...Bg4 13.Re1 c4 {preparing for Bf5-d3} 14.h3 Bf5 15.g4 (15.Nf3 Na6 16.d6 { is also good for White but I believe 15.g4 is      simpler}) 15...Bd3 16.Bxd3 cxd3 17.Qxd3 {White is a pawn up and Black does not  have sufficient compensation. White can defend the fourth rank with Re4  stopping the Black knights and the pawn on e5 can be supported with Nf3.  If Black plays Rc8 then stepping out of the pin with Kb1 avoids all  potential problems on the c-file.} 17...Na6 18.d6 Rc8 19.Kb1 Nb4 20.Qd1 Rxc3 21.bxc3 N4d5 22.Ne2 Qc8 23.Rhf1 {One  of many good moves. Qb3, Bg3, Qd3 and Qd4 are also all better for White.  As long as White keeps the pawn on e5 well protected Black cannot generate serious threats against the white king because the bishop on g7 will  remain a spectator.} 23...Nxc3+ 24.Nxc3 Qxc3 25.Qb3 {Black cannot  generate any threats without activating the bishop on g7. But this looks  difficult to do because f6 after Kh8 for instance gives White two  connect passed pawns on the 6th rank.}  *

