1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Bb4 {Black's idea is to put pressure on White's queenside before White can consolidate. One point is that if Black continues with Na5 then White cannot defend c4 with b3 because the knight on c3 would be hanging.} 10.Be2 {White develops normally.} (10.Rc1 { is interesting as well. Tillis gives} 10...Bg4 11.a3 Bxc3+ 12.bxc3 O-O 13.Bd3 Bxf3 14.gxf3 Qh4+ 15.Bf2 Qh3 { as annoying for White but after} 16.Rg1 { I would rather be White. Black's queen can become a     target Rg4-h4 and trying to open lines against the White king with} 16...f6 17.Rg4 { threatening Rh4 and Bxh7+} 17...g6 18.Rh4 Qg2 19.Qd2 { looks very dangerous for Black. White threatens Qh6 and Bxg6, and Ke2      followed by Rg1 is also possible.}) 10...Na5 {Probably Black's best move. Black threatens c4 before White is ready to defend it with b3.} (10...O-O { This is playable but it makes White job a bit easier because the knight on c3 is no longer pinned after} 11.O-O { This chapter contains a number of independent lines starting from this position but I do not think it is necessary to study them when starting with the Four Pawns Attack because Black's best option is to try to transpose back to the mainline.}) (10...Bxc3+ 11.bxc3 { will transpose to one of the other lines.}) 11.c5 Nd5 (11...Bxc3+ 12.bxc3 Nd5 13.Bd2 { transposes to 12...Bxc3}) (11...Nd7 12.Bg5 f6 13.exf6 Nxf6 14.O-O Bxc3 15.bxc3 O-O 16.Ne5 { +-  White is much better with the bishop pair, a stable pawn center, Black's misplaced knight on a5, the weak pawn on e6 and the control of the dark squares.}) 12.Bd2 Ne7 (12...c6 13.Nxd5 Bxd2+ 14.Qxd2 { The same motif as in the 9...Bg4 lines. Once Black is forced to recapture on d5 with a pawn here because the queen has to defend the knight on a5 Black's counterplay      against d4 is gone and the ideal outpost for the knight is no longer accessible.} 14...cxd5 (14...exd5 15.b3 O-O 16.O-O b6 17.Rac1 { the knight on a5 will have difficulties to get back into the game. In the mean time White can use his space advantage on the knigside to start an attack.}) 15.Qc3 { followed by b4 with a space advantage for White on both wings.}) (12...Bxc3 13.bxc3 c6 14.c4 Ne7 15.O-O { White can continue with Qe1-g3 and Nh4. If Black plays b6 then White can simply take on a5      essentially winning a pawn.}) 13.O-O O-O {As far as I am concerned I consider this the key position in this chapter. In this position Tillis only considers 14. a3 which is an inaccuracy because the square a3 is needed by White in order to answer b6 with Ba3. This will neutralize Black's counterplay on the queenside. After the correct 14. Bc1 Black will have an uphill struggle ahead because the attempt to generate counterplay with b6 is no longer effective as long as White can play Ba3.} 14.Bc1 {White threatens to move the knight away from c3 and then then trap the bishop with a3. So Black's next move is more or less forced.} (14.a3?! Bxc3 15.bxc3 h6 { Black creates an escape for the bishop, and will follow up with b6 to get enough counterplay on the queenside. If White allows bxc5 then White has to sacrifice a pawn or accept a ruined pawn structure on the queenside. Taking on b6 is also not ideal because Black gets counterplay on the a-file after axb6.}) 14...Bxc3 15.bxc3 Nac6 {trying to centralize the knight. But it is not so clear where this knight is going since the other knight already occupies e7. Still, this may be Black's best option.} (15...h6 { 15... h6 was Tillis' suggestion when I asked him about this     line. The idea is to give the bishop an escape square and then follow      up with b6 to get counterplay. But I don't think it solves Black's problems.} 16.Nh4 Bh7 17.Bd3 Nac6 (17...Bxd3 18.Qxd3 { +-  White can now start an attack with Qg3,          Qg4, Rf3}) (17...b6 18.Bxh6 gxh6 19.Rf6 { and White wins. The idea of Rf6 is          to stop any freeing attemps with f6 or f5. The knight on h4 and          the bishop on d3 make sure that Black cannot block the g-file by          putting a piece on g6. White simply continues with Qg4 Qxd3 if          Black takes on d3 and Raf1.}) 18.Bxh7+ Kxh7 19.Qg4 Qd5 20.Rf3 { +-  White can continue with Rg3, Be3      and Raf1.}) (15...Qd7 16.Nh4 Be4 17.Rf4 { If the bishop leaves the diagonal b1-h7      then White can attack with Bd3, Rg4-g3 and Qg4, Bg5, Raf1. If the      bishop retreats to g6 then Black has an unpleasant choice after Nxg6.      If he takes with the f-pawn then e6 is weakened, and if he takes with      the h-pawn then doubling heavy pieces on the h-file can be very      dangerous.}) 16.Qe1 b6 17.Ba3 {and White is better because bxc5 is not threatening to destroy White's pawn structure on the queenside.}  *

