1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 (9.Be2 { This move can be used to avoid the 9...Bg4 line. However, I do not think that avoiding this line is necessary and since Black can use the move order with a quick Bf5 and e6 to 'force' White to play an early Nf3 it is in any case not possible to avoid this line completely. Furthermore Black can go for the independent line} 9...Qh4+ 10.Bf2 Qe7 11.a3 (11.Nf3 Qb4 { gives Black enough counterplay against White's queenside.}) O-O-O 12.Nf3 g5 { which leads to some complications. Black threatens g4 and Nxd4. White is probably better after} 13.c5 { but all this seems unnecessary.}) 9...Bg4 {A logical move. Black puts pressure on d4.} 10.Be2 Bxf3 {If Black does not take now the the game will transpose to other lines.} 11.gxf3 {This is forced if White wants to protect the pawn on c4.} (11.Bxf3 Nxc4 12.Bf2 { gives White some compensation for the pawn but not enough for an advantage.}) 11...Qh4+ 12.Bf2 Qf4 {The key position for this chapter. If you remember White's next move and the reason for playing it you should be fine.} 13.c5 {White wants to exchange queens. But the immediate Qc1 would help Black to get counterplay against d4.} (13.Qc1 Qxc1+ 14.Rxc1 O-O-O { and now} 15.c5 Nd5 16.Nxd5 Rxd5 { keeps the square d5 alive as an outpost for the knight.}) 13...Nd5 (13...Nd7 14.Qc1 { Black cannot put pressure on d4 any longer.} 14...Qxc1+ 15.Rxc1 { The knight on d7 is a long way away from d5 because the squares b6 and f6 are not available.}) 14.Nxd5 exd5 {This is the reason why White played c5 before offering to exchange queens with Qc1. Now the square d5 is no longer available for the knight and once queens have been exchanged White can freely push pawns on both wings.} 15.Qd2 Qxd2+ (15...Qf5 { Avoiding the exchange allows White to activate his bishops and to consolidate the space advantage with} 16.O-O-O a5 17.f4 Nb4 18.b3 { and the knight on b4 can be driven back any time.}) 16.Kxd2 {White can place his bishops on d3 and e3 and then start pushing his pawns on both wings with f4-f5 or b4-b5.}  *

