1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Nb4 {Black gains a tempo with the threat Nc2+ in order to attack White's      center with c5. However it turns out that the delay in development      the bishop remains for a few more moves on f8 is enough to give      White an advantage.} (9...Be7 10.Be2 Nb4 11.Rc1 c5 { transposes to the mainline 10. Rc1 c5 11.Be2 Be7}) 10.Rc1 {This is forced.} 10...c5 {This is Black's idea. Any other move would give White an advantage      after a3 or Be2.} 11.Be2 (11.Qb3 { This move may be even stronger. But since Black can also choose the move order 9...Be7 10. Be2 Nb4 it is simpler to just study 11.Be2.}) 11...cxd4 (11...Be7 12.a3 cxd4 13.Nxd4 Nc6 (13...Na6? 14.b4 Bg6 15.c5 { White is already winning because the knight on a6 is not well-enough defended.} 15...Nd5 (15...Nd7 16.c6 { and Black cannot capture on c6 because the knight on a6 would be hanging.}) 16.Nxd5 Qxd5 17.Qa4+ Kf8 18.c6 { again making use of the shaky support of the knight on a6.}) 14.Nxf5 exf5 (14...Qxd1+ { does not help.} 15.Rxd1 exf5 16.Nb5 { White has a clear advantage.}) 15.O-O O-O 16.c5 Nd7 17.b4 { A typical position for this line. White is better. He has the bishop pair, a space advantage and the more mobile pawn majority.}) 12.Nxd4 Bg6 {The key position for this chapter. Here it is necessary to remember that 13.h4 is the best move and also that 
- if Black creates an escape for the bishop with h6 or h5 then c5 is much better for White. If you remember the line until 16. Nxe6 then you are probably fine.  
- 13...Qc7 with the idea Qxe5 can be simply answered with 14. h5 Qxe5 15. Qd2 when the bishop on g6 runs out of squares
- 13...Bc5 14.h5 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 is better for White regardless of whether Black plays Bd3, Nc2+ or Nd3+.} (12...Nc6 13.Nxf5 exf5 14.O-O { and White is clearly better. Black's attempt to win a pawn with} 14...Qxd1 15.Rcxd1 Nxe5 16.Rxf5 Nexc4 { leads to disaster after} 17.Bxb6 Nxb6 18.Bb5+ Ke7 19.Re1+) 13.h4 Bc5 {Black allows h5 hoping to get enough counterplay in the center.} (13...Qc7 { Black wants to get counterplay with Qxe5} 14.h5 Qxe5 (14...Bf5 15.Nxf5 exf5 16.Bd4 { White has too many threats: a3 and Nd5, Nb5 and also c5}) 15.Qd2 { Bg6 is in trouble} 15...Bf5 16.a3 Nc6 17.Nxc6 bxc6 18.Bf4 { with the idea g4 is better for White.}) (13...h5 { 13...h6 can be answered in exactly the same way. The only real differences are that Black does not have the option Rh6 available and that White can use the square h5 as well. Both are in White's favor.} 14.c5 Nd7 (14...Bxc5 15.Bb5+ Nd7 16.Nxe6 fxe6 17.Bxc5 { With a clear advantage for White. White's bishops are well placed and if Black tries to exchange them with} 17...Nd3+ 18.Bxd3 Bxd3 19.Qxd3 Nxc5 { then} 20.Qg6+ { followed by O-O is close to winning for White.}) 15.Qa4 Bxc5 16.Nxe6 fxe6 17.Bxc5 Nc2+ 18.Rxc2 Bxc2 19.Qxc2 Nxc5 20.Qg6+ { Here we see the reason why weakening the square g6 with h4 was      necessary. With the pawn still on h7 Black would be better.} 20...Kf8 (20...Kd7 21.b4) 21.b4) 14.h5 Bxd4 15.Bxd4 Nc2+ (15...Nd3+ 16.Bxd3 Qxd4 17.Be2 Qxd1+ 18.Rxd1 Bf5 19.O-O { followed by g4 and/or c5 is good for White.}) (15...Bd3 16.Bc5 Bxe2 17.Kxe2 Qxd1+ (17...Qc7 18.Qd6 Qxd6 19.Bxd6 { followed by Nb5, Ne4 or Rhf1 is good for White.}) 18.Rcxd1 { with a better endgame for White.}) 16.Rxc2 Bxc2 17.Qd2 {White needs to keep the bishop on d4 protected. Now White threatens Bxb6 followed by Qxc2.} 17...O-O {The only chance for Black.} 18.h6 (18.Bxb6 axb6 19.Qxc2 { is possible but gives Black counterplay after} 19...Qg5) 18...Bg6 {saving the bishop.} 19.hxg7 Kxg7 20.Qe3 {followed by Ne4 gives White a strong attack. Black's dark squares are extremely weak.}  *

