1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Qd7 10.Be2 Rd8 {In this line Black plans to put pressure on d4 as quickly as possible without giving White as easy a target as after O-O-O.} 11.O-O Bg4 {The key position of this line. Black is threatening to win the pawn on d4 with Bxf3 and Nxd4. White has several interesting options now. The three most popular moves are Ng5, c5 and d5. Neither of which I find wholly convincing so I chose the rarely played 12.b3. The idea of b3 is straightforward: to securely defend c4 to keep the knight on b6 out of the action and to free the bishop on e2 to recapture on f3. This also indirectly protects d4 because b7 will hang as well.} (11...Be7 { Too slow. After} 12.d5 { White is much better already.} 12...exd5 13.Bxb6 { A common motif. White ensures that Black cannot recapture on d5 with the knight.} 13...axb6 14.cxd5 Bc5+ { Clearing the square e7 for the knight with tempo.} 15.Kh1 Ne7 { still the best option but White can secure the pawn on d5 now and is much better after} 16.Nh4 {.}) 12.b3 {White secures c4 to be ready to recapture on f3 with bishop, after which d4 will be indirectly protected because b7 hangs as well. Both 12. c5 and 12. Ng5 are playable as well. But these lines are more complicated without giving White a larger advantage.} 12...Bb4 {Black gains a tempo to prepare castling.} (12...Be7 13.Qe1 { If Black allows White to protect d4 with Rad1 then White has a clear advantage. So taking on f3 is the only real option.} 13...Bxf3 14.Bxf3 Nxd4 15.Bxb7 { White is better. If he prepares his attack on the kingside with Rd1, Be4 and perhaps Kh1, Black will have no counterplay.}) (12...Bxf3 13.Bxf3 Nxd4 14.Bxb7 c5 15.Be4 { followed by Qg4, Rae1 and, if necessary, Kh1 leaves Black also without counterplay.}) 13.Ne4 {White offers a pawn sacrifice.} 13...O-O {the most prudent option.} (13...Bxf3 14.Bxf3 Nxd4 { Black wins a pawn but White gets more than      enough compensation after} 15.Bh5 { because with the queen on d7, the      pawn move g6 is not possible because of the fork on f6.} 15...Nf5 (15...O-O 16.Qg4 { is winning for White. None of Black's minor          pieces is ready to defend the king and White threatens Nf6+,Bh6 or         Rad1.}) 16.Qg4 { The bishop is indirectly protected Qxg7, Nf6+.} 16...Rf8 17.Bf2 { +-  Black's king is stuck in the center and Black's pieces on the     queenside are useless at best. White can slowly increase the pressure      with Qf4,Bf3 and g4 pushing back Black's only well placed piece.}) 14.Kh1 {White has time for this quiet move avoiding all tactics on the h1-a7      diagonal.} 14...Be7 {A logical defensive move.  Taking the pawn with} (14...Bxf3 15.Rxf3 Nxd4 { is risky for Black. After} 16.Rh3 { White threatens Bd3 and Nf6+ after which the attack cannot be stopped.} 16...Nf5 { The only defense.} 17.Qc2 { Now Black cannot take on e3 because Nf6+ is mate in 2. If Black plays f6 to get some breathing room on the kingside then Nc5 is strong while after other moves White can play Rf1, Bg1 and then Bd3 with a strong attack.}) 15.Qe1 Bxf3 {After other moves White simply plays Rad1 with a clear advantage.} 16.Rxf3 Nxd4 17.Rh3 {White has a strong attack.}  *

