1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Qd7 10.Be2 O-O-O 11.O-O Kb8 {The best move as far as I am concerned. Black prevents tactics along the c8-h3 diagonal before deciding how to continue.} (11...Bg4 { Not as critical as in the line with Rd8 instead of O-O-O. Here White gets a good position with c5 and a quick b4.} 12.c5 Nd5 13.Nxd5 Qxd5 14.h3 (14.b4 { is also good. I prefer to insert h3 Bh5 to have the option of playing g4 later. But whether or not to insert h3 is mostly a matter of taste.}) Bh5 (14...Qe4 { This intermediate move does not help Black.} 15.Qb3 Nxd4 16.Nxd4 Bxe2 { otherwise White can take on g4.} 17.Rf4 { White is winning.}) 15.b4 { +-  followed by Qc1 or Qd2 and Rae1.}) (11...Be7 { Too slow. The maneuver d5, Bxb6 and cxd5  works well for White because the black king is still on c8.} 12.d5 exd5 13.Bxb6 { The standard way to prevent Black from playing Nxd5 after cxd5.} 13...axb6 14.cxd5 Bc5+ 15.Kh1 Nb4 16.Nd4 { 16. d6 or 16. Nh4 are good moves as well. But note that the tactics work out in White's favor only because the black king is still on c8.} 16...Bxd4 (16...g6 17.Nxf5 gxf5 18.Bf3 { Black has no attack on the kingside while White can slowly start an attack with Rfe1, a3 and b4. Note that White's bishop on f3 is perfectly placed for both attack and defence.}) 17.Qxd4 Nc2 18.Qc4 Nxa1 19.Rxf5 Nc2 20.Rf1 Kb8 21.Qe4 { The knight on c2 is trapped.}) 12.a4 {The key move. The insertion of the moves a4 and a5 is quite strongly in White's favor.} 12...a5 {Trying to block White's pawns on the queenside with pieces does not work.} (12...Na5 13.c5 Nd5 14.Nxd5 Qxd5 (14...exd5 15.Qe1 Nc4 16.Bc1 { threatening to trap the knight with b3 gives White a clear advantage.}) 15.b4 Nc6 (15...Nc4 16.Bf2 { The knight on c4 is trapped.}) 16.Qd2 { +-  followed by b5 with a clear advantage.}) (12...Bb4 13.a5 Nxa5 (13...Bxa5 14.Qb3 { +-  followed by Rfd1 and d5 or c5 is much better for White. Black's minor pieces are providing convenient targets to speed up White's attack.}) 14.c5 Nd5 15.Nxd5 Qxd5 16.Rxa5 Bxa5 17.Qa4 Qe4 18.Kf2 { and Black's bishop on a5 is running out of squares.}) 13.Qe1 {The idea is to transfer the queen to g3 from where it can defend the pawn on e5 as a preparation for the pawn break d5 and also indirectly eyeing the king on b8. The diagonal g3-b8 is likely to be opened soon since without f7-f6 Black has difficulties to generate counterplay on the kingside. While the queen is on e1 there are also tactics involving Nb5 and Qxa5 even if Black can win an exchange with Nb4-c2 in a few lines.} (13.Qb3 { followed by Rac1 and Rfd1 or Rad1, and Nb5 and possibly d5 and d6 trying to exploit the shaky position of the knight on b6 is also an interesting option.}) 13...Bb4 (13...Nb4 14.Nb5 { the complications favor White. But note that it is      essential that the moves a4 and a5 were included. For instance} 14...Nc2 15.Qxa5 Nc8 16.Qc3 { gives White a pawn and a strong attack for the     exchange once Black takes on a1.}) 14.Qg3 {White can start an attack with Nb5 and d5. The queen on g3 helps to      protect e5 and can join the attack after d5 and e6 or in case Black      tries to create counterplay with f6.} 14...f6 15.d5 Nxe5 16.Nxe5 fxe5 17.Na2 Qe7 {The bishop does not have any good retreats.} (17...Be7 18.d6! { is very unpleasant for Black be cause the pawn cannot be taken without losing a piece.}) 18.Nxb4 Qxb4 19.Qxe5 {White is much better here. g7 is hanging and d6 is a strong threat as well because cxd6 leaves the knight on b6 without protection and if a piece takes on d6 then White has the fork c5.}  *

