1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Be7 {Black's best option as far as I am concerned. Black prepares to castle and then attacks White's center with f6. I believe White can keep some advantage but has to be careful not to allow the freeing move e5.} 10.Be2 (10.d5 exd5 11.cxd5 Nb4 12.Nd4 { is a complicated line which involves an exchange sacrifice by White but does not promise White any advantage.}) 10...O-O (10...f6 11.O-O fxe5 (11...O-O { transposes to the mainline.}) 12.d5 { White is much better.}) 11.O-O f6 (11...Bg4 12.b3 { followed by h3, Qd2 and Rad1 is better for White. If Black tries} 12...f6 13.exf6 Bxf6 14.Ne4 { then White is clearly better because Black has to surrender his dark-squared bishop or control of the important square e5 with Be7.}) 12.exf6 Bxf6 13.Qd2 Qe7 (13...Qe8 14.Bg5 { After White exchanges the dark squared bishops and      plays Qe3 and Rad1 White has a small but definite and stable      advantage. Black's pawn on e6 is weak, e5 is a nice outpost for the      knight and White has a space advantage.}) (13...Qd7 { This is not the best square for the queen.} 14.Rad1 Rad8 15.Qc1 Kh8 16.Kh1 Qe8 17.h3 Bg6 18.Rfe1 Rf7 19.Bf1 Qf8 20.Bg1 { White      is better here. See the model game Moser-Beim.}) 14.Rad1 Rad8 15.Kh1 {This is necessary to avoid e5.} (15.Qc1 { A popular move but inaccurate because Black has the promising pawn sacrifice} 15...e5 {.}) 15...h6 (15...e5 { is too early.} 16.d5 Nd4 (16...e4 17.Ng5 Nd4 18.Nxh7 Nxe2 19.Nxf6+ Rxf6 20.Qxe2 { +-  White is much better.}) (16...Bg6 17.c5 e4 18.d6 cxd6 19.cxb6 exf3 20.Bxf3 axb6 21.Nd5 { +-  Black's position is collapsing.}) 17.Nxd4 exd4 18.Bxd4 Bg5 19.Qe1 { +-  White is clearly better.} (19.Bc5 Qxc5 20.Qxg5 { is also good.})) 16.Qc1 Kh8 (16...e5 { Still too early.} 17.d5 Nd4 (17...Nb4 18.Ne1 { +-}) (17...e4 18.Ng1 { +-}) 18.Nxd4 exd4 19.Bxd4 Bg5 20.Qa1 { +-  Black has no compensation for the pawn. Note that if the White king were still on g1 then Black could exchange the dark-squared bishops with tempo with Be3+ and then exploit the shaky position of the bishop on e2 with Na4.}) (16...Rd7 17.Bg1 Rfd8 { too early. With the king still on g8 White can     play} 18.d5 exd5 19.cxd5 { because the pawn is indirectly protected. If Black takes then White can win an exchange with Bc4.}) 17.h3 Bh7 {The most popular move but I think increasing the pressure on d4 with Rd7 and Rfd8 is more logical.} (17...Rd7 18.Bg1 Rfd8 { As far as I am concerned this is the key position in this line. If White protects d4 with Qf4 then Black can increase the pressure on d4 with g5 and Qg7. So the next move is more or less forced.} 19.c5 Nd5 (19...Nc8 20.Bb5 a6 21.Bxc6 bxc6 22.Rde1 { gives White a clear advantage after Ne4 or Ne2-f4.}) 20.Bb5 { This is a complex position where Black has not yet      equalized.}) (17...e5 { Still too early. White gets a clear advantage in all lines.} 18.d5 Nd4 (18...Nb4 19.Ne1 { +-}) (18...e4 19.Nh2 { +-}) 19.Nxd4 exd4 20.Bxd4 { +-}) 18.Bg1 Rd7 (18...Rfe8 { again the most popular move but I do not understand why.} 19.b3 e5 { If this move would work then Rfe8 would make sense but White is just better after} 20.d5 { The Black knight as no good square.}) (18...e5 { is better for White after} 19.d5 Nb4 20.a3 e4 (20...Na6 21.b4 { is close to winning for White.}) 21.Nd2 Nd3 22.Bxd3 exd3 23.Rde1) 19.Rfe1 Rfd8 (19...Qf7 20.Bf1 { White can continue to improve his position with      moves like b3, Ne4 and Qe3.}) (19...Qd8 20.Qe3 Qe7 21.Bf1 { +  This is the type of position White is     aiming for. Black has no counterplay, a weak pawn on e6 and the knight     on b6 is misplaced.}) 20.d5 exd5 21.cxd5 Bxc3 (21...Nxd5 { does not work either because of} 22.Rxd5 Rxd5 23.Nxd5 Rxd5 24.Bc4 { and White is clearly better.}) 22.bxc3 Nxd5 23.Bb5 Qf6 24.Bxc6 bxc6 25.Bd4 Qf4 26.Ne5 Qxc1 27.Rxc1 Re7 28.Bc5 {White wins an exchange.}  *

