1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black      play cxd4 then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for      White.} 7.d5 {avoiding the exchange and also preventing Nc6.} 7...e6 {Black now uses d5 as a new target.} 8.Nc3 exd5 {Slower moves don't make sense. White will be better after Nf3.} (8...Qh4+ 9.g3 Qd4 10.Qxd4 cxd4 11.Nb5 { +-  followed by d6 and Nbxd4 gives White an extra pawn and a better position.}) 9.cxd5 {The starting point of this line. If Black can develop his pieces,      especially the bishop on f8, then the pawns on e5 and d5 may become      difficult to defend. If on the other hand White manages to prevent      Black from developing for long enough then the extra space may be used     for starting an attack.} 9...c4 {Black wants to put more pressure on White's center with Bb4 or target White's dark squares on the kingside with Bc5.} (9...Qh4+ 10.g3 Qd4 11.Bb5+ { White wants to play Qe2 without locking the bishop on f1.} (11.Qxd4?! { With exd5 and cxd5 included this does not work because d5 hangs after the knight on c3 moves.} 11...cxd4 12.Nb5 Nxd5 { =+}) 11...Bd7 12.Qe2 { White is clearly better. The threats Nf3 and e6 are not easy to deal with.}) 10.d6 {The key move. White is much better now because Black cannot break up      White's dominating pawns in the center. White's plan is      straightforward: complete development with Bf4, Nf3 and Be2. If Black      attacks the center too early with f6 then Nb5 with the threat Nc7+ is      strong.} 10...Nc6 11.Bf4 {As usual we postpone Nf3 until Black's light-squared bishop has moved. In this position Black's can try to break up White's pawns on e5 and d6 with f6 or fianchetto his dark-squared bishop with h6 and g5.} 11...Be6 (11...g5 12.Ne4 { is winning for White.}) (11...f6 { Black tries to break down White's center immediately.} 12.Nb5 fxe5 13.Be3 Qh4+ (13...Bf5 14.Nf3 { The simplest solution. White simply completes his development.} 14...Rc8 (14...a6 15.Nc7+ { followed by Bxb6 is the idea behind Be3.}) 15.Be2 a6 16.Nc7+ Rxc7 17.dxc7 Qxc7 18.O-O { +-  Black has two pawns for the exchange but the pawn on c4 will likely fall soon and it is not so easy for Black to get his king to safety.}) 14.g3 Qe4 15.Nc7+ { The complications turn out in White's favor. Black's king is much more vulnerable than White's. For details check      the lines in this chapter.}) 12.Nf3 Nd7 {Black plans to increase the pressure on e5 with Qa5, g6 and Bg7. But      after Ng5 White is simply better.} (12...f6 13.Nd4 { and White is close to winning.}) (12...h6 13.Nd4 { +-  followed by Be2, Ne4 and O-O with a clear      advantage for White.}) 13.Ng5 Ncxe5 {what else? White is threatening Nxe6 followed by Bxc4.} (13...Ndxe5 { transposes after} 14.Nxe6 fxe6 15.Bxe5 Nxe5 16.Qh5+) 14.Nxe6 fxe6 15.Bxe5 Nxe5 16.Qh5+ Nf7 (16...Ng6 17.O-O-O Bxd6 18.Qb5+ Ke7 19.Bxc4 { White is winning.      Black's extra pawn is meaningless and after Rhe1 White's position is      simply overwhelming.}) 17.Bxc4 Bxd6 (17...Qxd6 18.Bb5+ Ke7 19.O-O { White is winning.}) 18.O-O O-O 19.Bxe6 {Black cannot defend the knight on f7. White can play Rae1 or Nd5 if      necessary.}  *

