1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 {Black attacks White's center immediately. If White would let Black      play cxd4 then defending the pawn on e5 could become a problem for      White.} 7.d5 g6 {This is the modern way to play the 6...c5 variation. Originally      7...e6 was the only move played.} 8.Nc3 Bg7 9.Bf4 {White postpones the development of the knight on g1 until the black light-squared bishop has moved to avoid the pin Bg4, or at least to win a tempo.} 9...O-O 10.Qd2 {White still postpones Nf3 and prepares to castle queenside.} 10...e6 (10...Bf5 11.h3 { White prepares to trap the bishop with g4 in case Black plays e6.} 11...N8d7 (11...e6 12.O-O-O { +-  Again White has to wait with playing g4 since Black could play Qh4+ and after the exchange of queens the bishop can escape via c2 and a4.}) 12.Nf3 { White could play g4 immediately but since Black can free the bishop with the pawn sacrifice g5, White first develops. Now g4 is threatened and it's not clear how Black should defend.} 12...Qc7 13.Qe3 { does not change anything.}) (10...N8d7 11.Nf3 { White has a clear advantage. Black cannot put any additional pressure on White's center.}) (10...Bg4 { preventing O-O-O for one move.} 11.h3 { White has a clear advantage, after the bishop retreats and White castles long.}) 11.O-O-O exd5 (11...f6 12.Nf3 exd5 13.cxd5 fxe5 14.Bxe5 Bxe5 15.Nxe5 { White is      clearly better. Black is behind in development and developing his      queenside is difficult. Bf5 runs into g4 and d7 is needed by the      knight on b8. Also the d-pawn cannot be blockaded on d5 because Qd6      runs into one of Nc4, Nb5 or Ne4.}) 12.cxd5 {The key position of this line. If Black plays too slowly then White can play h3, possibly g4, Nf3 and Bh6 with a strong attack.} 12...Re8 {Black delays the decision of how to develop his queenside for one more move while increasing the pressure on e5.} (12...Bg4 13.Re1 c4 { preparing for Bf5-d3} 14.h3 Bf5 15.g4 Bd3 (15...Bd7 16.Bh6 { +-  Black has no counterplay whatsoever.}) 16.Bxd3 cxd3 17.Qxd3 { White is a pawn up and Black does not have sufficient compensation. White can defend the fourth rank with Re4      stopping the Black knights and the pawn on e5 can be supported with Nf3. If Black plays Rc8 then stepping out of the pin with Kb1 avoids all potential problems on the c-file.}) (12...Na6 13.h3 { +  White can continue with Nf3, g4 and Bh6.} 13...Nb4 14.g4 { stopping Bf5} 14...Bd7 15.Nf3 Rc8 16.Kb1 { White is better. White can complete his development with Be2 an then start to attack with Bh6 and Bxg7.}) (12...Bf5 13.h3 c4 { preparing an escape for the bishop.} 14.g4 Bd3 15.Bxd3 cxd3 16.Qxd3 N8d7 17.Nf3 { +-  White has an extra pawn and dominates the center.}) 13.Bg5 Qc7 (13...f6 14.exf6 Bxf6 15.Nf3 { +-  White has ideas like Bb5 and Rhe1 or Qf4-h4.}) 14.Bb5 Bd7 (14...Rxe5 15.d6 { traps the queen.}) (14...N8d7 15.e6 fxe6 16.d6 Qb8 17.h4 { White's attack cannot be      stopped with most of Black's pieces hiding on the queenside.}) 15.Nf3 {White has a clear advantage.} 15...a6 {Other moves also lead to a clear advantage for White.} (15...Bxe5 16.Nxe5 Qxe5 (16...Rxe5 17.Bf4 { is winning}) 17.Rhe1 { White is winning.}) (15...Bxb5 16.Nxb5 Qd7 17.Nd6 Rxe5 18.Nxe5 Qxd6 19.Rhe1 { White won the exchange and has a strong passed pawn on d5.} (15...Na6 16.d6 Qc8 17.Bxd7 Qxd7 (17...Nxd7 18.Nd5 { White is winning.}) 18.Bf6 { with a strong attack for White.})) 16.d6 Qc8 17.Bxd7 N8xd7 (17...N6xd7 18.Nd5 { The threats Ne7+ and Nc7 are too strong.}) (17...Qxd7 18.Bf6 { White starts a mating attack. The plan is to exchange bishops and play Ng5 and Rhf1.} (18.Qf4 { followed by Rhf1 or Rhe1 is also very strong. If Black exchanges queens with Qf5 then White is much better after Qxf5 gxf5.})) 18.Rhe1 {Develops the last piece and protects e5. The pawn on e5 cannot be defended but the weakened dark squares, the passed pawn on d6 and the move Nd5 with the threats Ne7 and Nc7 give more than enough compensation.}  *

