1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 g6 {This is the modern way to play against the Four Pawns Attack. Black plans to play Bg7 and Be6 and if White plays d5 then Black can play Bf5 followed by c6.} 6.Nc3 Bg7 (6...dxe5 { This exchange is a little bit premature. White can now play c5 without having to worry about dxc5.} 7.fxe5 Bg7 8.c5 { White gains more space and more importantly stabilizes the center because Black's main attacking idea, the move c5, is no longer possible.} 8...Nd5 9.Bc4 c6 10.Qb3 O-O 11.Nf3 { White could win a pawn by taking on d5 here. But Black would get easy development and pressure against d4 in exchange for the pawn. So it is better to keep up the pressure with the text move. White can start a strong attack with O-O, Ne4 and Nfg5.}) 7.Be3 Be6 {The modern main line.} (7...O-O { Castling is premature here. White gets full control of the      center with} 8.c5 N6d7 (8...dxc5 9.dxc5 Qxd1+ 10.Rxd1 N6d7 11.Nd5 { wins immediately.}) 9.h4 h5 { otherwise White gets a strong attack with h5.} 10.Nf3 { White has a large space advantage.}) (7...dxe5 8.dxe5 (8.fxe5 { is possible but here Black gets strong counterplay with c5 because e5 is weak.}) 8...Be6 (8...Qxd1+ 9.Rxd1 c6 10.c5 Nd5 11.Nxd5 cxd5 12.Rxd5 Be6 13.Rd2 Bxa2 14.b4 Be6 15.Nf3 { followed by Nd4 is better for White.}) 9.Qxd8+ Kxd8 10.Nf3 Nxc4 (10...Bxc4 11.Bxb6 Bxf1 12.Bxc7+ Kxc7 13.Rxf1 { +-  is much better for White. All White's pieces are active, the black king is exposed and Black's dark squared bishop is shut in.}) 11.Bf2 { White has more than enough compensation for the pawn.} 11...f6 (11...Nb6 12.Ng5 { followed by Nxe6 and O-O-O}) (11...Nxb2 12.Ng5 { Black's knight is trapped and the bishop on e6 needs to defend f7.}) 12.O-O-O+ { +-  followed by Nd4 and e6.}) 8.Rc1 {White will have to play d5 sooner or later to fight for an advantage.     If White plays d5 too early then Black can get rid of White's center      pawns with c6. So White wants to play d5 only after Black has attacked     the center with c5. But as soon Black castles the pawn on c4 will be      hanging. So White prepares b3 by protecting the knight on c3 which      otherwise would be undefended on the long diagonal after b3 and d5.} 8...O-O (8...dxe5 9.fxe5 Nxc4 10.Bxc4 Bxc4 11.Qa4+ b5 12.Nxb5 Bxb5 13.Qxb5+ Nd7 14.Nf3 Rb8 15.Qe2 Nb6 16.O-O { leads to a small but definite advantage for White. Black's pawns and light squares on the queenside      are very weak. Doubling the rooks on the c-file with Rc5 and Rfc1 in combination with Qa6, Qc4 or Ra5 will very likely win a pawn in the long run.}) (8...Nxc4 9.Qa4+ b5 (9...Qd7 10.Bxc4 Qxa4 11.Nxa4 Bxc4 12.Rxc4 b5 13.Rxc7 { +  with a very unpleasant endgame for Black.}) 10.Nxb5 Nxe3 11.Nxc7+ Kf8 12.Nxa8 Bd5 13.Nc7 Bxg2 14.Nh3 Bxh1 15.Ng5 { and White has too many threats: Ne6+, Qb3, e6.}) 9.b3 dxe5 (9...Na6 10.h3 c5 11.d5 Bc8 12.Nf3 { White's space advantage is      considerable. Black can put pressure on e5 with} 12...Nd7 { But} 13.Bd3 dxe5 14.f5 { gives White a strong attack.}) (9...c5 10.d5 { will very likely transpose since delaying dxe5 only      gives White extra options.}) 10.fxe5 c5 11.d5 Bf5 (11...Bc8 12.Nf3 Bg4 13.Bxc5 Bxf3 (13...N8d7 14.Bf2 Nxe5 15.Be2 Nxf3+ 16.Bxf3 Bxf3 17.Qxf3 { is better for White after O-O and Rfd1. Attacking the center with e6 and exd5 will likely lose an exchange after Bc5.}) 14.gxf3 Bxe5 15.Bg2 Na6 16.Be3 e6 17.O-O exd5 18.f4 Bg7 19.Nxd5 { The bishop pair and Black's misplaced knight give White a small but definite advantage.}) 12.Be2 {White prevents Nd7 with this move because g4 would trap the bishop if     there is a knight on d7.} (12.Nf3 N8d7 { allows Black to comlete his development and put      pressure on White's center.}) 12...Bxe5 (12...Na6 { Black protects c5 but gives White enough time to protect      e5 in return.} 13.Bf4 Qb8 (13...Nd7 14.g4 g5 15.Bxg5 Bg6 16.Nf3 Nxe5 17.Nxe5 Bxe5 18.h4 Bg3+ 19.Kf1 { followed by h5 or Kg2 and Rf1 is clearly better for          White.}) 14.Nf3 Nd7 (14...Bg4 15.d6 Bxf3 16.Bxf3 exd6 17.exd6 { is better for White.          The bishops are too strong in combination with the pawn on d6.}) 15.O-O Nxe5 16.Kh1 { +-  The pin is quite unpleasant for Black.}) 13.Nf3 Bd6 {Black wants to keep the pawn.} (13...Bg7 14.Bxc5 { +-  followed by O-O, Bf2 or Be3 and Nd4.}) (13...Bxc3+ 14.Rxc3 N8d7 15.O-O { The weak dark squares are more than      enough compensation for the pawn. White can continue with Bh6, Ng5 and     perhaps g4.} 15...e6 16.dxe6 Bxe6 17.Ng5 { +-  with ideas like Ne4-d6      and Bh6.}) 14.O-O N8d7 15.Bh6 Nf6 (15...Re8 16.g4 Bxg4 17.Ng5 { is much better for White. Blocking the      f-file with} 17...Bf5 { does not work because White has} 18.Rxf5 gxf5 19.Qf1 e6 20.Qg2 { and now the open g-file decides the game.}) 16.Qd2 {White has many ways to continue the attack. Ng5 and g4 possibly      preceded by h3, Ng5 and Rxf5, h3 and g4, Nh4 or also simply Bxf8 if      Black does not move the rook.}  *

