1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 (2...Ng8 { This move is playable but slightly worse than Nd5. A sample continuation is:} 3.d4 d6 4.f4 Bf5 5.Nf3 e6 6.Bd3 Ne7 7.O-O dxe5 8.fxe5 Nbc6 9.c3 { with a clear plus for White. The pawn on c3 stops Black's counterplay. This is the reason why Black usually tries to 'lure' the pawn to c4 by playing Nd5 on move 2.}) (2...Ne4 { This loses a pawn for no compensation or leads to a serious weakening of the kingside.} 3.d4 { White threatens to trap the knight on e4 with f3.} 3...e6 { Black prevents the immediate f3 with the threat Qh4 and also prepares an escape route for the knight.} (3...f6 { looks rather ugly but prepares the escape route g5-f7 for the knight.} 4.Nh3 d5 5.f3 Bxh3 6.fxe4 Be6 7.c4 { and White gets full control of the center.}) 4.Nh3 { White again threatens to trap the knight with f3.} 4...h6 5.Qg4 { Now White wins a pawn.} 5...d5 6.f3 h5 7.Qf4 g5 { This is the only move which saves the knight.} 8.Nxg5 Nxg5 9.Qxg5 { White is a healthy pawn up.}) 3.d4 d6 (3...c6 { White gets a comfortable position after} 4.c4 Nc7 5.Nc3 d6 6.f4 g6 7.Be3 Bg7 8.Nf3 O-O 9.Qd2) (3...c5 4.c4 Nb4 5.d5 d6 6.a3 N4a6 7.Bf4 Nd7 8.Nf3 { White is better.      White can complete his development with Nc3, Qe2, O-O-O or Be2 and O-O     while it is not so easy for Black to find good squares for his pieces.}) (3...Nb6 4.c4 d6 5.f4 { transposes to the mainline.}) 4.c4 Nb6 (4...Nb4 5.Qa4+ N8c6 6.d5 b5 7.cxb5 Nd4 8.Na3 { Black loses one of his     knights.}) 5.f4 {The simplest way to deal with various move orders is just to remember     to answer Bf5 with Nc3, Nc6 with Be3, e6 with Nf3 and dxe5 with fxe5.} 5...Bf5 {this usually tranposes to the mainline.} (5...e6 6.Nc3 dxe5 (6...d5 7.c5 N6d7 8.b4 b6 9.Rb1 { +-  White gets a large space          advantage and Black has difficulties finding squares for his          pieces.}) 7.fxe5 c5 8.d5 { transposes to the chapter 6...c5,e6}) 6.Nc3 dxe5 (6...e6 7.Nf3 Na6 { A speciality of Baburin. The idea is to attack White's center with c5.} 8.a3 (8.Bd3 { is also good but the resulting positions are not so easy to play.}) c5 9.dxc5 dxc5 (9...Nxc5 10.b4 Ne4 11.Nxe4 Bxe4 12.exd6 { and Black cannot recapture on d6 because of the fork c5}) 10.Qe2 { with the idea Be3, Qf2, Be2 and O-O is good for White.}) 7.fxe5 e6 (7...Nc6 8.Be3 e6 9.Nf3 { transposes to the mainline.}) 8.Nf3 Bb4 (8...Nc6 9.Be3 { transposes to the mainline.}) (8...Be7 9.Be2 { also transposes to the main lines after Nc6 or O-O and Nc6 by Black.}) 9.a3 {Simplest. Since retreating with the bishop just gives White the useful move a3 for free, Black is 'forced' to take on c3 after which attacking the center with c5 loses its sting.} (9.Bd3 { is a good option as well. But just as after Baburin's Na6 it is more complicated.}) 9...Bxc3+ 10.bxc3 c5 {the reason for keeping the knight on b8.} (10...Nc6 11.Bd3 Bxd3 12.Qxd3 { followed by O-O is better for White.}) 11.Bd3 cxd4 (11...Bxd3 12.Qxd3 { followed by O-O, possibly a4-a5, and Ng5/d2-e4 is     also better for White.}) 12.Bxf5 exf5 13.cxd4 {White is better. He can continue with O-O and Qd3. If the Black queen leaves the diagonal d8-h4 then White has Nh4 and after g6 Black's dark squares will get very weak.}  *

