{What is White's best move?} 13.h4! {This is a move difficult to play over the board unless you know it is good. The idea is simply to trap the bishop with h5 and possibly g4. It turns out that counterplay with Qc7 or Bc5 is too slow and if Black tries to stop the h-pawn with h5 or at least create an escape for the bishop with h6 then c5 gives White a clear advantage. In these lines it is crucial that the square g6 is undefended, otherwise White could have played c5 immediately. For details click  here  (variation:9122944/#/13/w)  .} 13...h5 (13...Bc5 14.h5 Bxd4 15.Bxd4 { and the bishop on g6 is running out of squares.}) 14.c5 Nd7 (14...Bxc5 15.Bb5+ Nd7 16.Nxe6 fxe6 17.Bxc5 { Black can still try} 17...Nd3+ 18.Bxd3 Bxd3 19.Qxd3 Nxc5 { but} 20.Qg6+ { followed by O-O is winning.}) 15.Qa4 Bxc5 16.Nxe6 fxe6 17.Bxc5 Nc2+ 18.Rxc2 Bxc2 19.Qxc2 Nxc5 20.Qg6+ Kf8 21.b4 {If the knight moves then Qxe6 and O-O are winning.}  *

