{Should White play Qc1 or Kh1?} 15.Kh1! {White's king escapes possible checks on the g1-a7 diagonal. This is necessary to stop Black from equalizing with e5. For instance} (15.Qc1 { would allow} e5! 16.d5 Nd4 17.Nxd4 exd4 18.Bxd4 Bg5 19.Qa1 Na4! { This is the point of 15...e5. The knight on c3 has to defend the bishop on e2. But after moves like Rfe1 or Bf3 Black can first exchange the dark-squared bishops with Be3+ and then play Nxc3 to destroy White's pawn structure. This leaves White with a worthless extra pawn.}) { For details click  here  (variation:9119572/#/15/w)  .} 15...e5 16.d5 Nd4 17.Nxd4 exd4 18.Bxd4 Bg5 19.Qe1 {and White is better.}  *

