[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1k1r1b1r/pppq1ppp/1nn1p3/4Pb2/2PP4/2N1BN2/PP2B1PP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 6 12"]

{How should White continue?} 12.a4! {White has interesting alternatives here. For instance, I quite like a3 followed by b4 as well. However after looking at this position for a while I came to the conclusion that a4 is the best move. 
- Black cannot allow White to continue with a5 and a6. White's attack would be too fast.
- Stopping a5 with Bb4 does not work because White can play a5 anyway.
- if Black stops a4 with a5 then the pawn on a5 may become a target and the knight on b6 is no longer so stable. If White manages to break through in the center with d5 and d6 then the c pawn cannot capture on d6 because Bxb6 would win the knight on b6. 
For details click  here  (variation:9119572/#/15/w)  .} 12...a5 (12...Bb4 13.a5 Nxa5 (13...Bxa5 14.Qb3 { followed Rfd1 and d5 gives White a strong attack.}) 14.c5 Nd5 15.Nxd5 Qxd5 16.Rxa5 Bxa5 17.Qa4 { Black's bishop on a5 is running out of squares.}) 13.Qe1 {A slightly mysterious move.} (13.Qb3 { is good as well and may look more natural.}) { The queen is headed for g3. From there it supports the pawn break d5 because e5 is well-defended and it also eyes the king on b8. From e1 the queen can also take the pawn on a5 in case of Nb4-c2, giving White a strong attack.} 13...Bb4 {The complication after} (13...Nb4 14.Nb5 { favor White. But note that it is essential that the moves a4 and a5 were included. For instance} 14...Nc2 15.Qxa5 Nc8 16.Qc3 { with a strong attack.}) 14.Qg3 {White is ready to break through in the center with d5.}  *

[Event "Key position 04 (answer)"]
[Site "?"]
