{Should White exchange queens with Qc1?} 13.c5! {White wants to exchange queens in this position with Qc1 because without queens on the board the bishop pair and the space advantage would give White a pleasant advantage. However, playing Qc1 immediately would give Black counterplay.} (13.Qc1 ?! Qxc1+ 14.Rxc1 O-O-O 15.Rd1 Bb4 16.a3 (16.O-O ? Bxc3 17.bxc3 Na5 18.c5 Nd5 19.Rc1 { =+  Black's knights get too active.}) Bxc3+ 17.bxc3 Na5 18.c5 Nd5 19.Kd2 =) { For details click  here  (variation:9119584/#/13/w)  .} 13...Nd7 (13...Nd5 14.Nxd5 exd5 15.Qd2 Qxd2+ 16.Kxd2 { White has the bishop pair, a space advantage and can start pushing his pawns on either wing. Moreover, Black has no longer the outpost on d5 for his knight.}) 14.Qc1 Qxc1+ 15.Rxc1 {White can continue with f4 and Bf3, White has more space, the bishop pair and the black knight on d7 is badly placed.}  *

