{How should White continue?} 10.d6! {The key move. White is much better now because Black cannot break up White's dominating pawns in the center. White's plan is straightforward: complete development with Bf4, Nf3 and Be2 without allowing Black to develop his kingside.
For details click  here  (variation:9119502/#/10/w)  .} 10...Nc6 11.Bf4 Be6 (11...f6 12.Nb5 fxe5 13.Be3 { and Black cannot prevent Nc7+.}) 12.Nf3 Nd7 13.Ng5! {Black is in trouble. White threatens Nxe6 followed by Bc4 or Qg4. The remainder of this line shows what happens if Black takes on e5.} 13...Ncxe5 14.Nxe6 fxe6 15.Bxe5 Nxe5 16.Qh5+ Nf7 17.Bxc4 Bxd6 18.O-O O-O 19.Bxe6 {Black will lose the knight on f7.}  *

