1.e4 {This is one of my favorite games in the four pawns attack. White's play looks simple, but Black never manages to create any counterplay.} 1...Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Be7 10.Be2 O-O 11.O-O f6 12.exf6 Bxf6 13.Qd2 Qd7 {This is not the best square for the queen. If Black wants to put      pressure on d4 then doubling the rooks on the d-file is more      effective.} 14.Rad1 Rad8 15.Qc1 {White choses a setup similiar to the setup given against 13...Qe7.      But here the move order is not as important because with the queen on      d7 Black does not have the threat e5.} 15...Kh8 {Black avoids tactics along the a2-g8 diagonal in case White plays a      quick d5.} 16.Kh1 {Here exchanging dark-squared bishops with Bg5 was an interesting alternative.} (16.Bg5 Qe7 17.Bxf6 Qxf6 18.Qe3 { is better for White. Without the dark-squared bishop on f6 the weakness of the square e5 can become a problem for Black.}) 16...Qe8 {The queen is making room for the rooks. Rf8-f7-d7 is now possible.} 17.h3 Bg6 18.Rfe1 Rf7 19.Bf1 Qf8 {Black plans to play Bh5 and threaten Bxf3. If White plays g4 then the     knight on f3 loses its support and Black can create pressure on the      f-file.} 20.Bg1 {This game is given up to this point as a trainable  variation  (variation:9119567/#/20/w)  .} 20...Re8 (20...Bh5 21.g4 Bg6 22.Bg2 Nxc4 23.Rxe6 { was the better option for      Black. White's bishops in combination with d4-d5 put pressure on      Black's queenside but there is no concrete win yet.}) 21.Ne4 {Now White can exchange Black's important dark-squared bishop.} 21...h6 (21...Be7 22.Nfg5 Bxg5 23.Nxg5 { does not help either.}) 22.Nxf6 Rxf6 23.d5 exd5 {Otherwise Black just loses a pawn.} 24.Rxe8 Bxe8 25.cxd5 Ne7 26.Bd4 Rd6 (26...Rf5 27.Bd3 (27.Qxh6+ Kg8 28.Qe6+ { is possible as well but Bd3 is stronger.}) Rh5 28.Rf1 Nbxd5 29.Ng5 Qg8 30.Bh7 { Black's queen is trapped.}) (26...Rf4 27.Be5 Rf7 28.d6 cxd6 29.Qxh6+ Kg8 30.Qxd6 { White is      clearly better here as well.}) 27.Be5 Rxd5 28.Rxd5 Nbxd5 29.Qxh6+ Kg8 30.Qg5 {White can play Bd3 or Bc4 next followd by Nh4 or Nd4. Black has      trouble to contain White's active pieces.} 30...Nf5 {Black sacrifices a pawn to reduce the pressure.} (30...Ng6 31.Bxg7 Qxg7 32.Qxd5+ { does not help either.}) (30...c6 31.Bd3 Bd7 32.Nd4 { might have kept the game going for a      little bit longer.}) 31.Bxg7 Qxg7 32.Qxf5 {White has an extra pawn with the better position. Black's king is      wide open.} 32...c6 33.Qg5 {White could keep the queens on the board to make use of Black's open      king but the two connected passed pawns on the kingside are enough for     a win.} 33...Kf8 34.Qxg7+ Kxg7 35.Kg1 Bf7 36.a3 Ne3 37.Be2 Nd5 38.Kf2 Nb6 39.b4 Kf6 40.Ke3 Nd5+ 41.Kd4 Nf4 42.Bf1 Bd5 43.Ke3 Ne6 44.g4 b6 45.h4 c5 46.bxc5 bxc5 47.Bd3 {White's pawns cannot be stopped.}  1-0

[Result "1-0"]

1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 Bf5 6.Nf3 e6 7.Nc3 Na6 {Black wants to attack the center with c5. The knight move, a specialty of Baburin, prepares c5 while at the same time threatens Nb4. The downside is that it does not put any additional pressure on White's center pawns unlike dxe5 and Nc6.} 8.Bd3 {The  repertoire move  (variation:9119338/#/8/w)  (move here is 8.a3.)} 8...Bxd3 (8...Bg4 { Black tries to avoid the exchange of the light-squared bishops, but after} 9.h3 Bxf3 10.Qxf3 dxe5 11.dxe5 { White is clearly better.}) (8...dxe5 9.fxe5 Bxd3 10.Qxd3 c5 11.d5 exd5 { Black's idea here is that without the pawn on d6 he can win a pawn on d5 after cxd5 Nb4.} 12.O-O (12.cxd5 Nb4 13.Qe2 N4xd5 14.e6 fxe6 15.Ng5 { is also good for White but castling is even better.}) Nb4 (12...dxc4 13.Qe4 { White has many good moves here: Nb5, Rd1, Bg5}) (12...Nxc4 13.b3 Nb6 14.Ng5 { and f7 can no longer be defended.}) 13.Qe2 d4 14.Nb5 Be7 15.Nd6+ Bxd6 16.exd6+ Kf8 17.Ng5 { and again the weakness of f7 decides the game.}) 9.Qxd3 c5 10.d5 exd5 (10...Be7 11.dxe6 fxe6 12.exd6 Qxd6 13.Qe2 { White's knights have much better prospects Ne4, Ne5 than Black's.}) 11.cxd5 Be7 {Clearing the square c5 with tempo by attacking the white queen does not work.} (11...c4 12.Qf5! (12.Qe2 dxe5 13.Nxe5 Be7 14.Be3 O-O 15.Rd1 Bd6 16.O-O { is slightly better for White as well.}) g6 13.Qh3 Qc8 14.e6 { White's advantage is clear.} 14...fxe6 { If Black tries to keep the position closed with} (14...f5 { then} 15.g4 { is good for White.}) 15.dxe6 { White can start an attack with O-O and Ne4 or f5.}) 12.O-O O-O (12...c4 13.Qe2 O-O 14.Rd1 Nb4 { was probably a better option for Black but here White has a comfortable plus as well after} 15.Be3 {.}) 13.Qe4 Nc7 (13...f6 14.Rd1 { is also better for White. Note that} 14...fxe5 15.fxe5 dxe5 { allows} 16.d6 { followed by Qxb7, because} 16...Bxd6 { loses to} 17.Nb5 { or Ng5 and Qh4.}) 14.Rd1 Qe8 (14...f6 { hoping for} 15.e6? f5 { and Black is back, was Black best chance to stay in the game.}) 15.f5 {Black is suffocating now. White plans to continue with e6 or f6.} 15...Kh8 16.Bf4 {The immediate} (16.f6 gxf6 17.exf6 Bxf6 18.Qf5 { was also very strong.} 18...Qe7 (18...Qd8 19.Ne4 { followed by Ng5 wins.}) 19.Re1 Be5 20.Nxe5 dxe5 21.Rxe5 { and White can bring his remaining pieces quickly to the kingside with Ne4, Bf4 or Bh6 and Rae1 which should decide the game.}) 16...Rd8 17.f6 {Black is lost.} 17...gxf6 18.exd6 (18.exf6 Bxf6 19.Qf5 Qe7 20.Re1 { also wins.}) 18...Bxd6 19.Qf5 Bxf4 20.Qxf6+ Kg8 21.Qxf4 Qd7 (21...Nbxd5 22.Nxd5 Nxd5 23.Qg5+ { loses a piece.}) 22.Ne5 Qe7 23.d6 {Black resigns in view of} (23...Rxd6 24.Rxd6 Qxd6 25.Qg3+ Kh8 26.Nxf7+)  1-0

