1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Bb4 10.Be2 Na5 11.c5 Nd5 12.Bd2 Ne7 13.O-O O-O 14.Bc1 {This is the game which introduced the move Bc1.} 14...Bxc3 15.bxc3 Qd7 16.Nh4 Be4 17.Rf4 {Up to here this game was given as one of the  trainable lines  (variation:9119674)  (.)} 17...Bc6 (17...Bg6 18.Nxg6 fxg6 { Unfortunately for Black this is the only      move.} (18...hxg6 19.Rh4 { with the idea Rh3, Qe1 and Qh4 is winning for          White.}) (18...Nxg6 19.Rf3 { followed by Bd3-c2, Qd3 and h4-h5 and perhaps          Ba3 and Raf1 also leaves Black without counterplay.}) 19.Qd3 Rxf4 20.Bxf4 { followed by Raf1 is also rather depressing for      Black.}) 18.Bd3 (18.Rg4 f5 (18...Nd5 { as in the game does not work here because of} 19.Bh6) 19.exf6 Rxf6 20.Bg5 { was probably even stronger.}) 18...Nd5 19.Qh5 g6 20.Rg4 f5 21.Rg3 Rf7 {Black has managed to gain a little bit of space on the kingside but      White is still running the show.} 22.Bd2 b5 23.cxb6 cxb6 24.Nxg6 {Winning now because the othe rook can also join the attack with Raf1      and Rf3.} 24...hxg6 25.Rxg6+ Rg7 26.Rf1 Qf7 27.Rxg7+ Qxg7 28.Rf3 Be8 29.Qh4 Nc6 30.Bh6 Qh7 31.Rg3+ Bg6 32.Qg5 Nce7 33.c4 Nb4 34.h4 (34.Be2 { was good enough to win but in correspondence chess you have      enough time to check the flashiest moves carefully as well.}) 34...Nxd3 35.h5 f4 36.Rg4 Kf7 37.hxg6+ Nxg6 38.Qf6+ Ke8 39.Rxg6  1-0

