1.d4 d6 2.e4 g6 3.f4 Nf6 4.e5 Nd5 5.c4 Nb6 6.Nc3 dxe5 7.fxe5 c5 8.d5 Bg7 9.Bf4 O-O 10.Qd2 e6 11.O-O-O exd5 12.cxd5 Na6 13.h3 Bd7 {Black's idea is to play Na4 to exchange the well-placed knight on c3. This idea is logical but too slow in this position. The move} (13...Nb4 { is covered  here  (variation:9285199/#/13/b)  (.)}) 14.Nf3 Na4 15.Nxa4 Bxa4 16.b3 Bd7 17.Bh6 {Black has carried out his plan but now White can start to attack with     Bxg7 and h4-h5.} 17...Bh8 {A pragmatic decision. Black decides that keeping the bishop alive in      order to generate counterplay is  more important than the exchange.} 18.Bxf8 Qxf8 19.d6 (19.Bxa6 bxa6 20.Rhe1 { is also winning.}) 19...Nb4 20.a3 Nc6 {Black finally managed to put some pressure on e5.} 21.Bc4 {White can ignore the threat Nxe5 because f7 is weak.} 21...b5 {Gaining a tempo in order to take on e5.} (21...Nxe5 22.Nxe5 Bxe5 23.Rhf1 { is winning for White.}) 22.Bxb5 Nxe5 23.Nxe5 Bxb5 24.Qd5 (24.Rhe1 { is even stronger.}) 24...Bxe5 25.Qxe5 Re8 26.Qc3 Qh6+ 27.Rd2 Re3 28.Qc2 {Without the pawn on d6 Black would still have some chances to      continue the fight but here the threat d7-d8Q is too strong.} 28...Rd3 29.Qxd3 Bxd3 30.d7 {The d-pawn cannot be stopped.} 30...Qg5 31.Re1 Kg7 32.Re8 Qf6 33.Rxd3 {Black does not have a perpetual.} 33...Qa1+ 34.Kc2 Qa2+ 35.Kd1 c4 36.d8=Q Qb1+ 37.Kd2 Qb2+ 38.Ke3 cxd3 39.Rg8+ {Qh4 mate is next.}  1-0

