1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 c5 7.d5 e6 8.Nc3 exd5 9.cxd5 c4 10.d6 Be6 11.Nf3 Qd7 {Black postpones attacking White's center in order to castle quickly after Nc6. But starting with Nc6 would have been more flexible. This move is the  mainline  (variation:9119503/#/11/b)} ({in the chapter  6...c5  and  e6 .}) 12.a4 Qc6 {Now the knight can retreat to d7 but wasting two moves on developing      the queen to c6 cannot be good.} (12...a5 { This prevents a5 by White but beyond that does not make      much sense. White has the eternal outpost on b5 and Black can no      longer castle queenside.}) (12...Nc6 13.a5 Nc8 14.Bf4 { followed by Nb5 and the game is almost      over.}) 13.Bf4 {White simply continues developing while adding extra protection to      the pawns on e5 and d6.} 13...Qc5 {The queen moves again. Now Black can play Nc6 and finally castle queenside but starting with Nc6 at move 11 would have made much more sense.} 14.Ng5 (14.Ne4 { is another good move.} 14...Qa5+ 15.Bd2 Qd5 16.Nc3 Qc5 17.b4 { The most entertaining move. If the queen take then the dicovered      attacks Nb5 or Nd5 win.} 17...cxb3 18.Nb5 b2 19.Nc7+ Kd8 20.Rb1 Nc6 21.Rxb2 Nxe5 22.Nxa8 Nxf3+ 23.Qxf3 { and Black cannot even take the      knight on a8 because of Qxb7.}) 14...Nc6 15.Nxe6 fxe6 16.Qg4 O-O-O (16...Nd8 { The only way to defend e6 but hopeless. White can either      castle queenside followed by Be2 and Rhf1, or castle kingside after      Be2 while Black's king is stuck in the center.}) 17.Qxe6+ Nd7 18.O-O-O {The game is essentially over because e5 is indirectly defended by      Rd5.} 18...Qf2 19.Bg3 Qe3+ 20.Kb1 g5 (20...Nxe5 21.Re1 { also loses.}) 21.Bxc4 Bg7 22.Rhe1 Qb6 23.Nd5 {The remaining moves do not need any comments.} 23...Qa5 24.Bb5 Kb8 25.Bxc6 bxc6 26.Ne7 Qxa4 27.Rd4 Qa6 28.Qc4 Qxc4 29.Rxc4 Kb7 30.Rxc6 Rhe8 31.Rc7+ Kb6 32.Nd5+ Ka6 33.e6 Nf6 34.Nb4+ Kb5 35.Re5+ Kxb4 36.Be1+ Ka4 37.Rc4+ Kb3 38.Rb4  1-0

