1.e4 Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6 9.Nf3 Bg4 10.Be2 Bxf3 11.gxf3 Qh4+ 12.Bf2 Qf4 13.c5 Nd7 (13...Nd5 14.Nxd5 exd5 15.Qd2 { also gives White a small but definite      advantage. Once the pawn is on d5 there is no longer an outpost for      the knight and it is much more difficult for Black to put pressure on      d4. White's space advantage and bishop pair will make Black's      defensive task challenging.}) 14.Qc1 {Once the knight has moved to d7 exchanging queens is no longer a      problem. Black cannot put pressure quickly on d4 and it will take some     times for Black's knights to reach good squares.} 14...Qf5 (14...Qxc1+ { is covered  here  (variation:9119584/#/14/b)  (.)}) 15.Qb1 Qxb1+ (15...Qf4 16.Qe4 { does not help.}) 16.Rxb1 O-O-O 17.f4 {White has several plans here. He can expand on the queenside with      b4-b5, try to get rid of the of the weakness on d4 with Bf3 and d5, or     open lines on the kingside with f5.} 17...g6 {Black stops f5.} 18.Bf3 {Now White plans to play b4 and d5.} 18...Ne7 {Black tries to get a knight to d5.} 19.Bh4 {White stops the knight from reachin d5.} 19...Re8 20.Bxe7 Rxe7 {White had give up his bishop pair to stop the knight from reaching      d5. Also Black's pieces are highly uncoordinated.} 21.c6 {Better was b4-b5 and c6 to establish a pawn on c6. The pawn on f4 can     be defended with Ne2 in case Black plays Bh6.} 21...bxc6 22.Bxc6 Bh6 23.O-O Rd8 24.Rbd1 f6 25.Kg2 {White steps out of the way of a potential Be3+ after fxe5.} 25...Nb8 26.Ba4 fxe5 27.fxe5 Kb7 28.Rf3 a5 29.Ne4 Ka7 {The bishop on a4 is perfectly placed to prevent Black's rooks from entering the game.} 30.Nc5 Na6 31.Nb3 Rb8 32.a3 Rb6 33.Rf2 {With b2 defended the pawn on a5 is hanging.} 33...Ka8 34.Nxa5 c5 {This loses immediately but other moves are not really any better.} 35.dxc5 Nxc5 36.Rd8+ Rb8 37.Rxb8+ Kxb8 38.Nc6+ Kc7 39.Nxe7 Nxa4 40.Rf7 Kd8 41.Rxh7  1-0

